1
00:00:01,682 --> 00:00:04,173
- (eerie music playing)
- (whimpering)

2
00:00:21,368 --> 00:00:24,428
(screams)

3
00:00:28,809 --> 00:00:30,902
Following the sign
to Camp Crystal Lake

4
00:00:30,944 --> 00:00:33,606
can only mean one thing...
bad luck.

5
00:00:33,647 --> 00:00:35,706
For her, not for us.

6
00:00:35,749 --> 00:00:39,549
You see in 1980 when
producer/director Sean Cunningham

7
00:00:39,586 --> 00:00:43,215
released a little film
into the world called "Friday the 13th,"

8
00:00:43,256 --> 00:00:45,281
not even he could have
imagined the success

9
00:00:45,325 --> 00:00:48,692
or the fame or the carnage
that would ensue.

10
00:00:48,729 --> 00:00:50,560
With 12 movies to date,

11
00:00:50,597 --> 00:00:52,189
an endless body count

12
00:00:52,232 --> 00:00:55,292
and over a half billion
in worldwide box-office dollars,

13
00:00:55,335 --> 00:00:57,428
"Friday the 13th" gave birth

14
00:00:57,471 --> 00:01:00,372
to one of the greatest
cinematic villains of our time.

15
00:01:00,407 --> 00:01:02,007
She doesn't know what she's in for.

16
00:01:02,242 --> 00:01:04,506
So lock up your cabin doors,
zip up your tents

17
00:01:04,544 --> 00:01:07,138
and make sure that
your car does indeed start,

18
00:01:07,180 --> 00:01:11,082
because tonight
he could be anywhere.

19
00:01:11,118 --> 00:01:13,552
So you wondering
who I'm talking about?

20
00:01:13,587 --> 00:01:16,055
His name was Jason.

21
00:01:16,089 --> 00:01:19,081
(blood splattering)

22
00:02:20,787 --> 00:02:23,221
(screaming)

23
00:02:26,626 --> 00:02:28,093
For some of us,

24
00:02:28,128 --> 00:02:31,825
the problems we have as adults
go back to our mothers.

25
00:02:31,865 --> 00:02:33,799
In the case of Jason,

26
00:02:33,834 --> 00:02:35,859
truer words
were never spoken.

27
00:02:35,902 --> 00:02:37,870
(man softly)
Kill kill kill...

28
00:02:37,904 --> 00:02:40,896
In the late '70s,
Steve Miner and I had made a couple

29
00:02:40,941 --> 00:02:42,465
of children's movies

30
00:02:42,509 --> 00:02:44,841
and neither one of them
was very successful.

31
00:02:44,878 --> 00:02:47,711
And we had to do something
to keep the lights on.

32
00:02:47,747 --> 00:02:51,376
And so we came up with this notion
of doing "Friday the 13th."

33
00:02:51,418 --> 00:02:54,114
We had a title and a need

34
00:02:54,154 --> 00:02:56,554
- to make some money.
- (shatters)

35
00:02:56,590 --> 00:03:00,048
The thing about the story
is that it's so profoundly simple.

36
00:03:00,093 --> 00:03:04,029
The longest part of the process
of creating the first "Friday the 13th"

37
00:03:04,064 --> 00:03:05,998
was figuring out the venue,

38
00:03:06,032 --> 00:03:10,025
so I had to find some territory
that was adult-free

39
00:03:10,070 --> 00:03:11,935
so that these kids would be
on their own

40
00:03:11,972 --> 00:03:13,496
and we could pick them off
one by one.

41
00:03:13,540 --> 00:03:15,531
My character was sort of like

42
00:03:15,575 --> 00:03:17,566
the Janet Leigh in "Psycho."

43
00:03:17,611 --> 00:03:19,579
I'm the setup character
to follow,

44
00:03:19,613 --> 00:03:21,774
but I didn't last too long.

45
00:03:21,815 --> 00:03:24,409
We ran into the woods
where it was safe.

46
00:03:24,451 --> 00:03:26,419
Cunningham:
We had this notion that these kids

47
00:03:26,453 --> 00:03:28,751
would be out at a summer camp
and would be threatened

48
00:03:28,788 --> 00:03:30,619
by some kind of serial killer.

49
00:03:30,657 --> 00:03:33,285
We would then be surprised
to discover

50
00:03:33,326 --> 00:03:35,089
who the serial killer was at the end.

51
00:03:35,128 --> 00:03:38,393
Mrs. Voorhees,
who is mighty pissed off

52
00:03:38,431 --> 00:03:40,456
that her son Jason

53
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:42,559
drowned while
a couple of counselors

54
00:03:42,602 --> 00:03:44,866
were off boning somewhere.

55
00:03:44,905 --> 00:03:47,567
The counselors weren't
paying any attention.

56
00:03:47,607 --> 00:03:50,974
They were making love
while that young boy drowned.

57
00:03:51,011 --> 00:03:54,208
The scariest moment
in the original movie

58
00:03:54,247 --> 00:03:58,047
is when Alice realizes

59
00:03:58,084 --> 00:04:00,985
that Pamela is the killer.

60
00:04:01,021 --> 00:04:03,148
Kill her, Mommy!

61
00:04:03,189 --> 00:04:05,384
Kill her!

62
00:04:05,425 --> 00:04:08,883
And that's the beginning
of the chase at the end of the movie.

63
00:04:08,929 --> 00:04:12,057
(screaming)

64
00:04:12,098 --> 00:04:14,259
And when we think all is quiet

65
00:04:14,301 --> 00:04:17,429
and she survived
that horrible Friday the 13th...

66
00:04:17,470 --> 00:04:21,236
The boy, is he dead too?

67
00:04:21,274 --> 00:04:22,741
Policeman: Who?

68
00:04:22,776 --> 00:04:26,109
The one who attacked me, the one
who pulled me underneath the water!

69
00:04:26,146 --> 00:04:29,638
Ma'am, we didn't find any boy.

70
00:04:29,683 --> 00:04:31,412
Then he's still there.

71
00:04:31,451 --> 00:04:34,249
And he certainly was.

72
00:04:34,287 --> 00:04:36,517
Lauren-Marie Taylor:
Before we started filming "Part 2,"

73
00:04:36,556 --> 00:04:39,320
they had us watch
the original "Friday the 13th,"

74
00:04:39,359 --> 00:04:41,589
which almost scared me off
to not doing the project,

75
00:04:41,628 --> 00:04:43,323
'cause it really freaked
me out.

76
00:04:43,363 --> 00:04:45,331
After the first one

77
00:04:45,365 --> 00:04:46,992
Jason had been created,

78
00:04:47,033 --> 00:04:49,763
so the notion of having a surprise

79
00:04:49,803 --> 00:04:53,204
as to who it is or what it is
changed completely.

80
00:04:53,239 --> 00:04:55,207
So what the stories became

81
00:04:55,241 --> 00:04:58,335
was sort of a ritualized telling

82
00:04:58,378 --> 00:05:01,347
of a group of young people
who go someplace

83
00:05:01,381 --> 00:05:03,975
- where they shouldn't go.
- (gasps)

84
00:05:04,017 --> 00:05:06,713
What are you kids
doing out here?

85
00:05:08,355 --> 00:05:10,880
We come back to Crystal Lake
to open up this camp again.

86
00:05:10,924 --> 00:05:13,688
The ghost of the past,

87
00:05:13,727 --> 00:05:15,285
Jason comes to haunt them.

88
00:05:15,328 --> 00:05:16,795
Todd:
And one by one,

89
00:05:16,830 --> 00:05:19,663
Jason Voorhees kills us

90
00:05:19,699 --> 00:05:22,133
and continues to do
what he does best.

91
00:05:22,168 --> 00:05:24,830
"Part 2" was basically
his journey

92
00:05:24,871 --> 00:05:27,999
of seeking revenge
over the death of his mother.

93
00:05:28,041 --> 00:05:30,737
And he's got her
decapitated head

94
00:05:30,777 --> 00:05:32,506
on his mantelpiece.

95
00:05:32,545 --> 00:05:34,979
He just keeps killing and killing.

96
00:05:39,619 --> 00:05:42,349
And that's the journey
that's taken us for 30 years.

97
00:05:42,389 --> 00:05:44,152
It's remarkable.

98
00:05:44,190 --> 00:05:47,023
Cunningham: I really thought
it wasn't gonna work the way it did,

99
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:49,654
and I'm delighted
to have been so wrong.

100
00:05:49,696 --> 00:05:53,063
"Friday the 13th Part III"...
we get the gimmick movie.

101
00:05:53,099 --> 00:05:56,330
"Friday the 13th III" in 3D,
and that is also the movie

102
00:05:56,369 --> 00:05:59,270
where Jason will choose
his infamous mask.

103
00:05:59,305 --> 00:06:01,637
The day after the events
in "Part 2"...

104
00:06:01,675 --> 00:06:03,666
so it's technically
Saturday the 14th,

105
00:06:03,710 --> 00:06:07,373
but don't tell anyone...
a group of teenagers

106
00:06:07,414 --> 00:06:10,611
all go up to the cabin
to visit Chris Higgins,

107
00:06:10,650 --> 00:06:12,117
little knowing that Jason

108
00:06:12,152 --> 00:06:14,746
is still out there killing everyone.

109
00:06:14,788 --> 00:06:16,881
Ugh!

110
00:06:16,923 --> 00:06:18,891
Through all the 3D movies
I've ever done,

111
00:06:18,925 --> 00:06:20,893
nobody talks about any of them.

112
00:06:20,927 --> 00:06:23,794
All they ever wanna
talk about is when can we see

113
00:06:23,830 --> 00:06:25,855
"Friday the 13th" in 3D.

114
00:06:27,367 --> 00:06:29,597
Ryan Rotten: Four is where things
start getting interesting.

115
00:06:29,636 --> 00:06:33,436
It starts to introduce
a protagonist Tommy Jarvis,

116
00:06:33,473 --> 00:06:36,931
who we'll start seeing
in other sequels.

117
00:06:36,976 --> 00:06:40,571
I was told that this was
gonna be the last of the series.

118
00:06:40,613 --> 00:06:43,776
And this again would be
about death at the end,

119
00:06:43,817 --> 00:06:45,284
because Jason was going to die.

120
00:06:45,318 --> 00:06:47,286
Barney Cohen: Jason had been hit
in the head with an axe.

121
00:06:47,320 --> 00:06:51,017
He had been carted off in an ambulance.
We pick him up almost in real time

122
00:06:51,057 --> 00:06:53,491
arriving dead at a hospital.

123
00:06:53,526 --> 00:06:55,926
And then Jason breaks out
of the morgue.

124
00:06:55,962 --> 00:06:59,454
Leave me alone!
(screaming)

125
00:06:59,499 --> 00:07:02,832
And then the kids
in the car arrive at the lake

126
00:07:02,869 --> 00:07:05,633
and bump into us.
There's skinny-dipping

127
00:07:05,672 --> 00:07:08,197
- and all kinds of things.
- Partying... we're partying on down

128
00:07:08,241 --> 00:07:10,300
and then we all got killed.

129
00:07:10,343 --> 00:07:11,935
In very quick succession.

130
00:07:11,978 --> 00:07:15,141
My character Rob
had a sister named Sandra,

131
00:07:15,181 --> 00:07:17,649
who was a counselor
at Crystal Lake in "Part 2."

132
00:07:17,684 --> 00:07:21,814
This dude looks like
he's been hunting Jason for years.

133
00:07:21,855 --> 00:07:25,655
The one time I saw the movie...
going to the opening night screening

134
00:07:25,692 --> 00:07:27,091
on Hollywood Boulevard...

135
00:07:27,127 --> 00:07:29,755
during the whole entire movie
just people screaming,

136
00:07:29,796 --> 00:07:32,924
it was like this cathartic
experience for everybody.

137
00:07:32,966 --> 00:07:34,160
It's a thrill ride.

138
00:07:34,200 --> 00:07:37,499
I remember that we're supposed
to think Corey Feldman's

139
00:07:37,537 --> 00:07:40,335
gonna pick up the torch
and be the next Jason.

140
00:07:43,977 --> 00:07:46,673
"Part 5" was truly
a departure

141
00:07:46,713 --> 00:07:49,238
because they went
in a totally different direction.

142
00:07:49,282 --> 00:07:53,116
They decide they're gonna set it
in a halfway house

143
00:07:53,153 --> 00:07:55,121
for weird fucked-up kids.

144
00:07:55,155 --> 00:07:57,885
And there's this dude
and he's killing the kids off

145
00:07:57,924 --> 00:07:59,824
and he's using Jason's mask.

146
00:07:59,859 --> 00:08:03,818
We don't see Jason in that movie,
except for hallucinations,

147
00:08:03,863 --> 00:08:07,128
flashbacks... that's it.

148
00:08:07,167 --> 00:08:10,227
When the film opened
it was opening, I think,

149
00:08:10,270 --> 00:08:12,067
in 2,000 theaters
across the country.

150
00:08:12,105 --> 00:08:13,970
In 1984, that was a lot.

151
00:08:14,007 --> 00:08:16,475
Frank Mancuso called me
late that night...

152
00:08:16,509 --> 00:08:18,477
2:00, 3:00 in the morning,

153
00:08:18,511 --> 00:08:21,071
so excited,
saying these numbers

154
00:08:21,114 --> 00:08:23,947
are like the golden times.
This is unheard of.

155
00:08:23,983 --> 00:08:26,383
Shavar Ross:
When the supposed Jason fell,

156
00:08:26,419 --> 00:08:30,150
I love the part where
he just goes right through those spikes.

157
00:08:31,891 --> 00:08:34,018
Because you can just see the dummy

158
00:08:34,060 --> 00:08:36,722
just going right on the spike.

159
00:08:36,763 --> 00:08:38,060
Another piece of advice,

160
00:08:38,097 --> 00:08:40,793
don't allow the overweight
mentally-handicapped son

161
00:08:40,834 --> 00:08:43,860
of the local ambulance driver
to get hacked to shit over a candy bar.

162
00:08:43,903 --> 00:08:46,167
Because chances are
that driver's gonna turn

163
00:08:46,206 --> 00:08:48,231
into a Jason clone
and try to take people out.

164
00:08:48,274 --> 00:08:50,799
Adam Green: They brought him back
again in "VI," and he killed Horshack

165
00:08:50,844 --> 00:08:52,709
at the beginning,
which was awesome.

166
00:08:52,745 --> 00:08:54,508
And he was kind of like
Frankenstein because a lightning bolt

167
00:08:54,547 --> 00:08:56,674
that came out of nowhere
brought him back to life,

168
00:08:56,716 --> 00:08:58,809
and there was maggots on his face,
which was really cool.

169
00:08:58,852 --> 00:09:01,320
I think it was extremely violent.

170
00:09:01,354 --> 00:09:02,548
I mean, you look at it and you go,

171
00:09:02,589 --> 00:09:05,353
"Wow, there's tongue-in-cheek
in this. There's rock music in this."

172
00:09:05,391 --> 00:09:08,588
But Jason, in fact,
in this movie, bends people in half,

173
00:09:08,628 --> 00:09:11,597
twists their heads off,
does a triple beheading.

174
00:09:11,631 --> 00:09:15,192
I really didn't want it to be
just about you have sex and die,

175
00:09:15,235 --> 00:09:18,363
'cause that had been done. It's sort
of like you're in the wrong place

176
00:09:18,404 --> 00:09:20,463
at the wrong time kind of thing,

177
00:09:20,506 --> 00:09:23,805
and also try to have the characters
have a sense of humor.

178
00:09:23,843 --> 00:09:27,210
When Nancy's killed
and the American Express card floats

179
00:09:27,247 --> 00:09:29,807
out of her hand, inevitably
there was always some clown

180
00:09:29,849 --> 00:09:31,407
that would go,
"Don't leave home without it!"

181
00:09:31,451 --> 00:09:33,942
Kevin Spirtas:
In "Part VII," the girl whose got these

182
00:09:33,987 --> 00:09:36,888
extraordinary telekinetic powers

183
00:09:36,923 --> 00:09:40,086
resurrects him by throwing
her anger and her energy

184
00:09:40,126 --> 00:09:42,094
into the lake
where he's already been killed

185
00:09:42,128 --> 00:09:43,720
from a previous movie.

186
00:09:43,763 --> 00:09:47,324
She musters all of her
telekinetic ability to raise him

187
00:09:47,367 --> 00:09:49,597
and thus begins the story.

188
00:09:54,107 --> 00:09:56,905
That's what really made it different.
She had the psychic abilities

189
00:09:56,943 --> 00:09:59,468
which he had not fought before,
but realistically,

190
00:09:59,512 --> 00:10:02,413
the psychic stuff would have had
to have been in there anyway,

191
00:10:02,448 --> 00:10:04,712
because this monster
kept coming back.

192
00:10:04,751 --> 00:10:06,776
He's a surreal monster.

193
00:10:06,819 --> 00:10:09,811
Jason, played by Kane Hodder,
I believe, for the first time.

194
00:10:12,358 --> 00:10:14,417
"VII" starts the Kane Hodder era.

195
00:10:14,460 --> 00:10:16,985
Everything about the way
Kane Hodder played him

196
00:10:17,030 --> 00:10:20,363
makes him menacing
and yet he's human.

197
00:10:22,502 --> 00:10:25,630
Elizabeth Kaitan: I remember thinking,
"Wow, this is Jason!"

198
00:10:25,672 --> 00:10:28,334
I grew up watching this,
and here he is chasing me.

199
00:10:28,374 --> 00:10:30,137
(chokes)

200
00:10:30,176 --> 00:10:33,543
Since I was doing it for the first
time, there seems to be some anger there,

201
00:10:33,579 --> 00:10:36,639
some differences that you
didn't see in Jason before.

202
00:10:36,683 --> 00:10:39,811
The kids love
Kane Hodder's Jason.

203
00:10:39,852 --> 00:10:42,821
Rob Galluzzo: The coolest
teaser trailer to a movie ever

204
00:10:42,855 --> 00:10:45,790
was " Friday the 13th 8:
Jason Takes Manhattan."

205
00:10:45,825 --> 00:10:47,554
You get this trailer
where you don't know what is it

206
00:10:47,593 --> 00:10:49,652
and then they reveal that
it's Jason in the middle of the city.

207
00:10:49,696 --> 00:10:51,391
I live in New York.
I was stoked. I was like,

208
00:10:51,431 --> 00:10:53,626
"Oh my God. He's coming to New York.
He's coming to where I know."

209
00:10:53,666 --> 00:10:55,531
When they first brought me in
to do the movie,

210
00:10:55,568 --> 00:10:59,129
the first question I asked them was
does it have to be in Crystal Lake?

211
00:10:59,172 --> 00:11:02,164
Can I take Jason out
of Crystal Lake?

212
00:11:02,208 --> 00:11:04,768
The general plot
of "Friday the 13th Part 8"

213
00:11:04,811 --> 00:11:07,837
is a young woman
and her graduating class

214
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:12,044
of Crystal Lake High going
on a big cruise to New York.

215
00:11:12,085 --> 00:11:15,646
One by one,
the classmates are killed off.

216
00:11:15,688 --> 00:11:18,521
The single most amazing thing
that I've ever done

217
00:11:18,558 --> 00:11:21,994
as the character was shooting
the scenes in Times Square

218
00:11:22,028 --> 00:11:23,757
in "Jason Takes Manhattan."

219
00:11:23,796 --> 00:11:26,264
I felt like a rock star.

220
00:11:26,299 --> 00:11:28,358
(raspy breathing)

221
00:11:30,737 --> 00:11:33,672
"Part 9"...they went
from not having blood

222
00:11:33,706 --> 00:11:35,333
to not having Jason.

223
00:11:35,375 --> 00:11:39,004
There was something about Jason
transferring from body to body to body.

224
00:11:39,045 --> 00:11:42,242
Joe Lynch:
Then Jason comes back to life

225
00:11:42,281 --> 00:11:44,306
and to Crystal Lake
and is exploded

226
00:11:44,350 --> 00:11:47,615
and becomes a bunch
of demon-hearted baby things

227
00:11:47,653 --> 00:11:50,053
and decides to possess
a couple of people.

228
00:11:50,089 --> 00:11:53,354
And then gets thwarted again by " 21
Jump Street" himself Steven Williams.

229
00:11:53,393 --> 00:11:54,860
Adam Green:
He really wasn't in the movie.

230
00:11:54,894 --> 00:11:57,454
It was kind of other people. Then if
he was in a mirror, you could see him.

231
00:11:57,497 --> 00:11:58,964
And he could transport
into bodies.

232
00:11:58,998 --> 00:12:01,523
But the best part was when
he was this little worm thing

233
00:12:01,567 --> 00:12:04,832
and he went...
was it the girl from "Buck Rogers"?

234
00:12:04,871 --> 00:12:07,738
Is that who she was? He went
in her pussy and that was awesome.

235
00:12:07,774 --> 00:12:11,107
They basically tried
to create a mythology for Jason.

236
00:12:11,144 --> 00:12:14,841
There are a lot of Jason fans
who to this day

237
00:12:14,881 --> 00:12:17,748
are pissed off at me

238
00:12:17,784 --> 00:12:19,775
for blowing up Jason.

239
00:12:21,020 --> 00:12:24,456
James Isaac: "Jason X" takes place
400 years in the future.

240
00:12:24,490 --> 00:12:27,789
And a group
of science students,

241
00:12:27,827 --> 00:12:29,658
kids go on a field trip.

242
00:12:29,695 --> 00:12:31,788
These students go on.
They're on the planet.

243
00:12:31,831 --> 00:12:35,790
They're digging things up,
and of course they find Jason.

244
00:12:35,835 --> 00:12:38,565
Anyway, Jason wakes up
and of course does what Jason does.

245
00:12:38,604 --> 00:12:41,129
We set it up
that Kay-Em actually did kill him.

246
00:12:41,174 --> 00:12:42,664
This time he got killed, right?

247
00:12:42,708 --> 00:12:45,233
Then the nanobots
bring him together

248
00:12:45,278 --> 00:12:47,007
and now he's part machine,

249
00:12:47,046 --> 00:12:50,311
and so he's more unstoppable
than ever.

250
00:12:50,349 --> 00:12:53,944
To this day, still,
when people mention that movie,

251
00:12:53,986 --> 00:12:56,420
they're like,
"I love that fake boob scene!"

252
00:13:01,360 --> 00:13:04,955
All right, the story
of "Freddy vs. Jason" is a hybrid story.

253
00:13:04,997 --> 00:13:08,160
You're bringing these two
great characters together finally.

254
00:13:08,201 --> 00:13:10,465
Tony Timpone:
It took them literally decades

255
00:13:10,503 --> 00:13:13,199
before they came up with a story
that was strong enough

256
00:13:13,239 --> 00:13:14,968
to support these two characters.

257
00:13:15,007 --> 00:13:18,943
The premise of this movie
was for Freddy to use Jason

258
00:13:18,978 --> 00:13:20,673
to get his powers back.

259
00:13:20,713 --> 00:13:23,375
There came a point where
you had to choose a side.

260
00:13:23,416 --> 00:13:26,613
And I was a Jason guy, always.

261
00:13:26,652 --> 00:13:30,486
So for "Jason vs. Freddy,"
I didn't wanna see anything

262
00:13:30,523 --> 00:13:33,253
but Jason kick Freddy's ass.

263
00:13:33,292 --> 00:13:36,557
Lynch: If it wasn't for Alice killing
Mrs. Voorhees in that one film,

264
00:13:36,596 --> 00:13:38,063
none of this would happen.

265
00:13:38,097 --> 00:13:41,123
I like Jason Voorhees.
He has a backstory,

266
00:13:41,167 --> 00:13:43,499
and he has a reason
for being the way he is.

267
00:13:43,536 --> 00:13:46,369
What a messed up kid.

268
00:13:46,405 --> 00:13:49,169
I think that just
in the overall energy

269
00:13:49,208 --> 00:13:51,733
of trying to do it simple
and scary

270
00:13:51,777 --> 00:13:54,575
was the thing that drove
the whole process forward.

271
00:13:56,716 --> 00:14:00,277
After all that,
who could imagine that Jason,

272
00:14:00,319 --> 00:14:04,278
the bloodthirsty
indestructible force of nature,

273
00:14:04,323 --> 00:14:06,883
was at one time
an innocent kid

274
00:14:06,926 --> 00:14:08,655
just like the rest of us?

275
00:14:08,694 --> 00:14:11,128
Well, most of us.

276
00:14:11,164 --> 00:14:14,065
Jason not only witnessed
his mother's beheading.

277
00:14:14,100 --> 00:14:16,967
But he was shot and stabbed

278
00:14:17,003 --> 00:14:19,062
and burned and sent to hell

279
00:14:19,105 --> 00:14:21,596
and shot into outer space.

280
00:14:21,641 --> 00:14:24,166
I think to really
understand Jason

281
00:14:24,210 --> 00:14:26,007
you gotta go back
to the beginning...

282
00:14:26,045 --> 00:14:28,775
who he is,
where he came from,

283
00:14:28,814 --> 00:14:31,282
why he can't resist
a good kill.

284
00:14:36,055 --> 00:14:38,717
(man softly)
Kill kill kill...

285
00:14:38,758 --> 00:14:41,454
Does Jason have a soul?
I don't think so.

286
00:14:41,494 --> 00:14:45,021
He is not mindless.
I think actually that's something

287
00:14:45,064 --> 00:14:46,725
that the fans would like
to learn more about...

288
00:14:46,766 --> 00:14:48,427
what's going on in his head.

289
00:14:48,467 --> 00:14:50,458
Jason started
as a drowning victim.

290
00:14:50,503 --> 00:14:51,868
That's as simple
as you can make it.

291
00:14:51,904 --> 00:14:54,873
He's just a little boy
who was ignored

292
00:14:54,907 --> 00:14:57,933
by his camp counselors
and couldn't swim very well

293
00:14:57,977 --> 00:15:00,969
and drowned. And no matter
what movie you're talking about,

294
00:15:01,013 --> 00:15:02,981
he's still a victim.

295
00:15:03,015 --> 00:15:05,916
For any good villain,
there's always that sadness to them,

296
00:15:05,952 --> 00:15:08,512
and that thing where you can
almost feel bad for them.

297
00:15:08,554 --> 00:15:11,990
He didn't do anything wrong.
He didn't deserve to die.

298
00:15:12,024 --> 00:15:15,619
Jason was the outcast. Jason was
the little kid who got picked on.

299
00:15:15,661 --> 00:15:18,630
And now Jason's the one
who's getting the last laugh in a way,

300
00:15:18,664 --> 00:15:20,222
or the last slash.

301
00:15:20,266 --> 00:15:21,824
Who did it start with?
His mother.

302
00:15:21,867 --> 00:15:25,428
I'm Mrs. Voorhees,
an old friend of the Christies.

303
00:15:25,471 --> 00:15:28,235
The fact that she's a loon,
totally out of her mind

304
00:15:28,274 --> 00:15:30,834
and also channeling her son
and going...

305
00:15:30,876 --> 00:15:33,902
Kill her, Mommy.
Kill her!

306
00:15:33,946 --> 00:15:36,073
The idea for the character
came out

307
00:15:36,115 --> 00:15:38,083
of my own past.

308
00:15:38,117 --> 00:15:41,086
Mrs. Voorhees
is the mother I never had.

309
00:15:41,120 --> 00:15:44,112
She is the mother
who will kill people

310
00:15:44,156 --> 00:15:46,852
to avenge her son's death.
But, hey,

311
00:15:46,892 --> 00:15:48,883
if you're gonna have
a mother defend you,

312
00:15:48,928 --> 00:15:50,691
she might as well be crazy.

313
00:15:50,730 --> 00:15:53,790
Palmer:
They love Mrs. Voorhees.

314
00:15:53,833 --> 00:15:57,792
And I've said to people,
I say, " Why do you love her

315
00:15:57,837 --> 00:15:59,930
as much as you do
when she's supposed

316
00:15:59,972 --> 00:16:02,532
to be this dreadful human being?"

317
00:16:02,575 --> 00:16:06,511
And they say because
we understand why you did it.

318
00:16:06,545 --> 00:16:10,003
Mrs. Voorhees was
really not a murderess.

319
00:16:10,049 --> 00:16:13,348
All she was trying to do was
to protect other children

320
00:16:13,386 --> 00:16:15,286
from being drowned.

321
00:16:17,356 --> 00:16:19,381
One of the things that
really works for "Part 2"

322
00:16:19,425 --> 00:16:22,917
is that you do have this kind
of passing of the baton

323
00:16:22,962 --> 00:16:25,988
going from Mrs. Voorhees
to Jason.

324
00:16:26,032 --> 00:16:28,830
Basically, he is fueled
by vengeance

325
00:16:28,868 --> 00:16:30,392
for the death of his mother.

326
00:16:30,436 --> 00:16:33,633
See, it's this seeking
righteous vengeance

327
00:16:33,673 --> 00:16:36,301
that defines
the Jason character

328
00:16:36,342 --> 00:16:39,004
and also separates
Jason Voorhees

329
00:16:39,045 --> 00:16:42,572
from all the other horror icons.

330
00:16:42,615 --> 00:16:44,480
(screams)

331
00:16:44,517 --> 00:16:46,382
King:
Jason's misunderstood.

332
00:16:46,419 --> 00:16:48,046
What happens is

333
00:16:48,087 --> 00:16:51,853
when he watches
Alice kill his mother,

334
00:16:51,891 --> 00:16:55,657
I believe Alice unleashes
the monster in Jason.

335
00:16:55,695 --> 00:16:57,390
You feel bad for anybody
who has to see

336
00:16:57,430 --> 00:16:59,762
their mom get their head cut off
on a beach. I know I do.

337
00:16:59,799 --> 00:17:02,131
Barton:
So he finds this potato sack,

338
00:17:02,168 --> 00:17:04,466
throws it over his head,
cuts out his little eyehole

339
00:17:04,503 --> 00:17:07,563
and does his thing. He starts
plying his craft for the first time

340
00:17:07,606 --> 00:17:10,097
that he learned
from his mom.

341
00:17:10,142 --> 00:17:11,404
(screams)

342
00:17:11,444 --> 00:17:13,378
I think he observed the camp
after many years,

343
00:17:13,412 --> 00:17:15,676
kids coming and going.

344
00:17:15,715 --> 00:17:19,151
I think at one point that's
when he decided to do what he did.

345
00:17:19,185 --> 00:17:22,245
I think what he's doing
is protecting his home.

346
00:17:22,288 --> 00:17:25,849
And anybody that walks
into his territory is kind of doomed.

347
00:17:28,094 --> 00:17:31,552
Honestly, I don't think he's angry.
I think he's sad.

348
00:17:31,597 --> 00:17:33,622
Poor Jason was brought
into this world

349
00:17:33,666 --> 00:17:36,396
and he really had a tough start.

350
00:17:36,435 --> 00:17:38,767
Kaitan:
If your mother killed a bunch of people,

351
00:17:38,804 --> 00:17:41,068
you would be a very tragic child,
I would say.

352
00:17:41,107 --> 00:17:44,201
It's like kind of a Ted Bundy
upbringing.

353
00:17:44,243 --> 00:17:47,212
Here was this tortured soul

354
00:17:47,246 --> 00:17:48,838
who lived for years

355
00:17:48,881 --> 00:17:51,816
just on probably the revenge.

356
00:17:51,851 --> 00:17:53,910
I think Ginny kind of understood

357
00:17:53,953 --> 00:17:57,650
there's more to it than just
this demon guy.

358
00:17:57,690 --> 00:17:59,749
Jason, Mother is talking to you.

359
00:18:01,594 --> 00:18:05,086
By putting on his mother's sweater
and trying to speak like her,

360
00:18:05,131 --> 00:18:07,224
it almost confused him
for a second.

361
00:18:07,266 --> 00:18:09,928
King: You see him questioning,
is that my mother?

362
00:18:09,969 --> 00:18:13,063
He wanted to believe
his mother was still alive.

363
00:18:13,105 --> 00:18:14,902
I guess Jason was
a unique character.

364
00:18:14,940 --> 00:18:16,908
He wasn't just somebody

365
00:18:16,942 --> 00:18:20,343
who put on a facemask.

366
00:18:20,379 --> 00:18:22,176
He was a whole creature.

367
00:18:22,214 --> 00:18:25,081
Lynch: It's almost like Jason
is a personification

368
00:18:25,117 --> 00:18:27,745
of the dark side of all of us.

369
00:18:27,787 --> 00:18:30,153
I find in this character
elements of myself.

370
00:18:30,189 --> 00:18:32,350
And there are monstrous elements
of myself

371
00:18:32,391 --> 00:18:35,258
that are bent on self-destruction
and destroying others.

372
00:18:35,294 --> 00:18:37,125
And there are parts of myself
that feel wronged

373
00:18:37,163 --> 00:18:39,791
and I'm unjustly treated
and I'm the victim.

374
00:18:39,832 --> 00:18:43,324
He just hated everything
about people.

375
00:18:43,369 --> 00:18:46,702
His reason for killing
is just because he does.

376
00:18:46,739 --> 00:18:49,071
Don't reason with him.
He doesn't reason with you.

377
00:18:49,108 --> 00:18:51,975
It's all in his own head.

378
00:18:52,011 --> 00:18:53,501
He just does it.

379
00:18:53,546 --> 00:18:55,446
He's definitely
a tortured tragic soul,

380
00:18:55,481 --> 00:18:57,881
but the truth is you can't go
around life with this badge

381
00:18:57,917 --> 00:19:00,442
that you've been tortured
and kill and slash.

382
00:19:00,486 --> 00:19:04,047
At some point,
it's gotta stop.

383
00:19:04,089 --> 00:19:06,023
The main aspect

384
00:19:06,058 --> 00:19:08,856
that enhances
the otherworldly character

385
00:19:08,894 --> 00:19:12,057
of Jason is that
he's silent and faceless...

386
00:19:12,097 --> 00:19:14,497
like death... the death mask.

387
00:19:14,533 --> 00:19:16,831
It's plenty scary,
the mystery of the unknown.

388
00:19:16,869 --> 00:19:19,394
What is behind that
potato sack?

389
00:19:19,438 --> 00:19:21,406
In "Friday the 13th Part III,"

390
00:19:21,440 --> 00:19:25,240
Jason wears, for the very first time,
a hockey mask,

391
00:19:25,277 --> 00:19:28,735
which he has taken from Shelly

392
00:19:28,781 --> 00:19:32,012
when Shelly made the bad mistake
of walking into the barn

393
00:19:32,051 --> 00:19:33,518
carrying the hockey mask.

394
00:19:33,552 --> 00:19:35,713
And the moment when he puts
on the hockey mask

395
00:19:35,754 --> 00:19:38,814
and realizes it,
it's a great moment for the franchise,

396
00:19:38,858 --> 00:19:42,453
'cause it's like,
"What was I thinking?

397
00:19:42,495 --> 00:19:45,089
I should have been wearing
this all along. This is awesome."

398
00:19:45,130 --> 00:19:46,529
This dock behind me,

399
00:19:46,565 --> 00:19:50,399
this is where the legend
of Jason was born.

400
00:19:50,436 --> 00:19:53,405
This is the first time
we saw him step out

401
00:19:53,439 --> 00:19:55,566
in the hockey mask.

402
00:19:55,608 --> 00:19:57,075
The birth of Jason.

403
00:19:57,109 --> 00:20:00,442
There's something
to be said about

404
00:20:00,479 --> 00:20:02,777
putting a mask on

405
00:20:02,815 --> 00:20:06,774
and doing things
that you wouldn't normally do

406
00:20:06,819 --> 00:20:09,185
with that mask off.

407
00:20:09,221 --> 00:20:11,416
Katz:
Jason in "Part III" runs.

408
00:20:11,457 --> 00:20:14,290
That's the one where he runs.
Jason's a bit of a manic hillbilly

409
00:20:14,326 --> 00:20:17,295
in "III" still.
Got a little of that left over.

410
00:20:17,329 --> 00:20:19,729
After that he becomes
the slow methodical stalker.

411
00:20:19,765 --> 00:20:22,632
Todd Farmer: If he sees you,
he's not gonna stop.

412
00:20:22,668 --> 00:20:26,297
It's like a beacon.
Once he's popped in on you,

413
00:20:26,338 --> 00:20:28,306
he's gonna stay there
until he kills you.

414
00:20:28,340 --> 00:20:30,035
And it doesn't matter
what he has to use.

415
00:20:30,075 --> 00:20:33,602
He's terribly creative.
And he's got lots of weapons.

416
00:20:33,646 --> 00:20:36,046
He really had a thing
for knives,

417
00:20:36,081 --> 00:20:38,447
and he really had a thing
for machetes.

418
00:20:38,484 --> 00:20:40,975
He likes to puncture
through the body...

419
00:20:41,020 --> 00:20:42,385
He really likes spears.

420
00:20:42,421 --> 00:20:45,151
...sawing off heads,
twisting heads, crushing heads...

421
00:20:45,190 --> 00:20:47,715
Taylor:
He was really into anything

422
00:20:47,760 --> 00:20:50,627
that would splash blood.

423
00:20:51,931 --> 00:20:54,297
...punching heads off,
eyes popping out.

424
00:20:54,333 --> 00:20:55,630
I mean, he's a showman.

425
00:20:55,668 --> 00:20:58,000
It was really about
watching Jason do his thing.

426
00:20:58,037 --> 00:21:00,597
He was the protagonist
in these films.

427
00:21:00,639 --> 00:21:04,006
He has become
an anti-superhero.

428
00:21:04,043 --> 00:21:06,068
So we just gotta come up
with a cape

429
00:21:06,111 --> 00:21:08,944
for the Big J.

430
00:21:08,981 --> 00:21:11,347
If we can just get him
to do some good stuff, though,

431
00:21:11,383 --> 00:21:13,283
you know?
He's got the killing down.

432
00:21:13,319 --> 00:21:15,116
Jason's always been
the underdog,

433
00:21:15,154 --> 00:21:16,985
and everybody roots
for the underdog.

434
00:21:17,022 --> 00:21:19,582
Roday:
It's every nerd's dream to get killed

435
00:21:19,625 --> 00:21:21,957
and them come back
as a bad-ass

436
00:21:21,994 --> 00:21:24,258
and start taking out
all the stereotypes

437
00:21:24,296 --> 00:21:26,457
that pick on nerds.

438
00:21:26,498 --> 00:21:30,195
- Why do you do these stupid things?
- I have to.

439
00:21:30,235 --> 00:21:32,726
Carey More: I think he's a little bit
of a madman, perhaps.

440
00:21:32,771 --> 00:21:34,796
Well, he seems
a little superhuman also

441
00:21:34,840 --> 00:21:36,933
because he seems
to be able to revive

442
00:21:36,976 --> 00:21:40,377
and take almighty blows
with hatchets and stuff.

443
00:21:40,412 --> 00:21:43,176
Jason is a kid
who's just too stupid

444
00:21:43,215 --> 00:21:44,682
to know that he's dead.

445
00:21:44,717 --> 00:21:46,548
I think it's always
kind of inventive

446
00:21:46,585 --> 00:21:49,452
how we would bring Jason back.
I always loved that.

447
00:21:49,488 --> 00:21:53,185
It was almost like the cliffhangers
in the old serials.

448
00:21:53,225 --> 00:21:55,955
How does he live
to see another day?

449
00:21:58,030 --> 00:22:00,658
Something's gotta bring him back.
Why not lightning, right?

450
00:22:00,699 --> 00:22:02,030
We can blow him up.
We can cut him up.

451
00:22:02,067 --> 00:22:05,662
We can shoot him up. We can dice him up,
and he comes back for more.

452
00:22:05,704 --> 00:22:08,901
It's great that as times change,
audiences change.

453
00:22:08,941 --> 00:22:12,536
The creature, the monster, the villain, I
think is allowed to evolve.

454
00:22:12,578 --> 00:22:15,308
Jason is the 21st-century killer.

455
00:22:15,347 --> 00:22:17,645
He's good old blood and guts.

456
00:22:17,683 --> 00:22:19,981
Shepherd:
I think that Jason is both a monster

457
00:22:20,019 --> 00:22:22,453
and a victim.
This is a very deep character

458
00:22:22,488 --> 00:22:25,855
that survived this many episodes
in killings and destructions

459
00:22:25,891 --> 00:22:28,359
because he's larger than life.

460
00:22:28,394 --> 00:22:30,521
He's still that little troubled

461
00:22:30,562 --> 00:22:32,427
mentally-ill boy

462
00:22:32,464 --> 00:22:34,864
trapped in the large body
of a killing machine.

463
00:22:34,900 --> 00:22:38,802
He's become iconic in our lives.

464
00:22:38,837 --> 00:22:41,738
Jason has no expiration date.

465
00:22:46,345 --> 00:22:48,836
(whimpering)

466
00:22:53,085 --> 00:22:56,282
(screams)

467
00:22:58,590 --> 00:23:01,525
12 movies in three decades?

468
00:23:01,560 --> 00:23:04,085
That's enough sequels
to rival box-office legends

469
00:23:04,129 --> 00:23:06,825
like James Bond or Godzilla.

470
00:23:06,865 --> 00:23:08,765
"Friday the 13th" defined

471
00:23:08,801 --> 00:23:11,565
what is considered
the modern-day slasher.

472
00:23:11,603 --> 00:23:13,798
Looking at this guy,
it's no wonder why.

473
00:23:13,839 --> 00:23:16,501
But you know what?
It takes more than a body count

474
00:23:16,542 --> 00:23:18,840
to make a "Friday the 13th" movie.

475
00:23:22,748 --> 00:23:26,184
The formula is pretty specific
with a "Friday the 13th" movie.

476
00:23:26,218 --> 00:23:28,243
The first thing you need
in a "Friday the 13th" film

477
00:23:28,287 --> 00:23:30,278
is nubile young flesh.

478
00:23:30,322 --> 00:23:34,224
You have a bunch of teenagers
and they cannot be accessible

479
00:23:34,259 --> 00:23:36,159
by adult power authorities.

480
00:23:36,195 --> 00:23:37,924
They can't come in
and save them.

481
00:23:37,963 --> 00:23:40,898
You have to have a reason
for the kids to be out in the woods.

482
00:23:40,933 --> 00:23:43,629
It's the " Let's run out
into the woods,"

483
00:23:43,669 --> 00:23:45,796
and, " Ooh!
There's a killer loose."

484
00:23:45,838 --> 00:23:48,898
- The crazy old bastard.
- (screams)

485
00:23:48,941 --> 00:23:51,535
I'm the messenger of God.

486
00:23:51,577 --> 00:23:54,910
You're doomed if you stay here.

487
00:23:54,947 --> 00:23:57,780
These movies are made
for teenagers.

488
00:23:57,816 --> 00:24:01,775
And so the point of view is
