00:34:56,107 --> 00:34:58,268
And we not only
just storyboarded it out,

736
00:34:58,309 --> 00:35:01,472
but we had to have a false sink
with the camera underneath

737
00:35:01,513 --> 00:35:04,607
and a glass for the water
because I wanted to be able to see

738
00:35:04,649 --> 00:35:07,618
the face come toward
the camera, not frozen.

739
00:35:07,652 --> 00:35:11,418
- And then...
- Bam! Face salad.

740
00:35:11,456 --> 00:35:14,425
(shatters)

741
00:35:14,459 --> 00:35:17,155
That was technically
our most difficult kill.

742
00:35:17,195 --> 00:35:19,993
I think his favorite thing
is smashing heads together.

743
00:35:20,031 --> 00:35:21,760
My favorite Jason kill
that I've ever done

744
00:35:21,800 --> 00:35:23,859
is the sleeping bag.

745
00:35:23,902 --> 00:35:26,803
He bashed her against the tree,
I think, at least five times,

746
00:35:26,838 --> 00:35:29,306
but we minimized it
to once.

747
00:35:29,340 --> 00:35:31,638
And that was
actually more impactful.

748
00:35:33,511 --> 00:35:36,378
Savini: I cut his brain in half
in "Part 4." I created the monster.

749
00:35:36,414 --> 00:35:39,645
Thank you for letting me
kill the monster.

750
00:35:39,684 --> 00:35:41,777
- And this is...
- Joseph Zito.

751
00:35:41,820 --> 00:35:43,913
- The...
- Director of " Friday the 13th

752
00:35:43,955 --> 00:35:47,721
- Final Chapter."
- I'm Erich Anderson and I played Rob.

753
00:35:47,759 --> 00:35:50,523
And we're at the house
where we shot the movie.

754
00:35:50,562 --> 00:35:52,723
This is really the site
of the death of Jason.

755
00:35:52,764 --> 00:35:54,288
Right there.

756
00:35:54,332 --> 00:35:56,800
Zito: We have a big
special-effects makeup group.

757
00:35:56,835 --> 00:35:58,735
And they're all around.

758
00:35:58,770 --> 00:36:00,328
They're all around
and they're pumping blood

759
00:36:00,371 --> 00:36:02,305
and moving the tongue

760
00:36:02,340 --> 00:36:05,707
and working all
of the parts.

761
00:36:05,743 --> 00:36:09,509
The mask hits the ground,
and the machete is picked up here,

762
00:36:09,547 --> 00:36:12,539
and Tommy ends up
taking the machete

763
00:36:12,584 --> 00:36:16,350
and killing Jason
to die die die.

764
00:36:16,387 --> 00:36:18,252
Girl: Tommy!

765
00:36:25,897 --> 00:36:27,797
You maybe were expecting
something quick.

766
00:36:27,832 --> 00:36:30,392
Tommy hits him in the head
with the blade, the end?

767
00:36:30,435 --> 00:36:31,868
No, he slides down the blade.

768
00:36:33,271 --> 00:36:35,569
(gagging, screaming)

769
00:36:50,054 --> 00:36:52,045
(screaming)

770
00:36:56,060 --> 00:36:58,221
Not too shabby.

771
00:36:58,263 --> 00:37:01,323
But creating Jason's handiwork
is never an easy task.

772
00:37:01,366 --> 00:37:04,062
Neither was creating
Jason Voorhees.

773
00:37:04,102 --> 00:37:05,763
I should know.

774
00:37:05,803 --> 00:37:09,637
So what does it take to create
an unforgettable movie villain?

775
00:37:13,444 --> 00:37:16,436
I came up with the idea
for Jason's name

776
00:37:16,481 --> 00:37:18,449
'cause originally it was
gonna be Josh,

777
00:37:18,483 --> 00:37:21,008
but the more I worked
on the film and the creepier

778
00:37:21,052 --> 00:37:22,883
the whole subject of that got,

779
00:37:22,921 --> 00:37:25,412
I stuck with the "J"
and went to Jason.

780
00:37:25,456 --> 00:37:27,151
Tommy Savini,
who of course

781
00:37:27,191 --> 00:37:29,716
did all those
fabulous special effects,

782
00:37:29,761 --> 00:37:32,457
gave me some Polaroids
to look at.

783
00:37:32,497 --> 00:37:35,227
And he said,
"That's your son,

784
00:37:35,266 --> 00:37:38,394
Jason.
He's a mongoloid."

785
00:37:38,436 --> 00:37:40,563
I said, "He's what?"

786
00:37:40,605 --> 00:37:43,870
His features were really a guy I used
to see in my neighborhood,

787
00:37:43,908 --> 00:37:47,173
a homeless drunk guy,
one ear was lower than the other.

788
00:37:47,211 --> 00:37:49,907
He was almost
a Quasimodo kind of guy.

789
00:37:51,316 --> 00:37:53,614
Lehman:
The first thing they do is they take

790
00:37:53,651 --> 00:37:55,676
a cast of your head.

791
00:37:55,720 --> 00:37:59,178
There was fake teeth.
There was a glass eye.

792
00:37:59,223 --> 00:38:00,952
One thing people often ask is,

793
00:38:00,992 --> 00:38:03,460
"Was it specially made
to go underwater?"

794
00:38:03,494 --> 00:38:05,189
and stuff like that.

795
00:38:05,229 --> 00:38:06,662
No, it was just...

796
00:38:06,698 --> 00:38:09,428
it was a latex prosthetic.

797
00:38:09,467 --> 00:38:12,368
Daskawisz:
Once I put the bag over my head

798
00:38:12,403 --> 00:38:15,031
and I ran in the woods,
I couldn't see anything

799
00:38:15,073 --> 00:38:17,200
'cause the bag flopped
back and forth.

800
00:38:17,241 --> 00:38:20,677
And he came up with this idea...
we'll put double-faced tape here

801
00:38:20,712 --> 00:38:24,204
and here, and we'll hold it
right close to your eye.

802
00:38:24,248 --> 00:38:26,773
This way you'll see where
you're going, and it worked great.

803
00:38:26,818 --> 00:38:28,786
But from taking the tape
on and off,

804
00:38:28,820 --> 00:38:31,653
I had started to develop burns
on my face.

805
00:38:32,790 --> 00:38:35,020
Gillette:
First they cut off all your hair,

806
00:38:35,059 --> 00:38:37,857
and then they started to build
the face with little rubber forms

807
00:38:37,895 --> 00:38:40,830
they would glue on.
And they sent me to a dentist

808
00:38:40,865 --> 00:38:43,732
that created dental plates
that would go in

809
00:38:43,768 --> 00:38:45,736
that were sort of
the worst dental problems

810
00:38:45,770 --> 00:38:47,203
anyone could ever have.

811
00:38:47,238 --> 00:38:49,138
And they built the beard
and the hair,

812
00:38:49,173 --> 00:38:50,970
and they taped off the eye.

813
00:38:51,009 --> 00:38:54,137
It's sort of painful
to have all this stuff put on.

814
00:38:54,178 --> 00:38:58,137
The scene of "Friday the 13th: 2"
where Jason

815
00:38:58,182 --> 00:39:00,241
comes careening
through the window...

816
00:39:00,284 --> 00:39:04,243
they built a platform
outside the house.

817
00:39:04,288 --> 00:39:07,553
The platform was probably
four feet long.

818
00:39:07,592 --> 00:39:10,561
So we coordinated
how many steps it takes.

819
00:39:10,595 --> 00:39:13,393
So one, two, three... aggh!

820
00:39:13,431 --> 00:39:16,025
(screaming)

821
00:39:18,469 --> 00:39:21,370
At the time when this was created,
there was a serial killer

822
00:39:21,406 --> 00:39:23,101
running around in Texas.

823
00:39:23,141 --> 00:39:25,666
And he was killing people

824
00:39:25,710 --> 00:39:27,371
with a potato sack on his head.

825
00:39:27,412 --> 00:39:29,778
This could have been
the inspiration,

826
00:39:29,814 --> 00:39:32,977
which I believe the potato sack
is a little scarier

827
00:39:33,017 --> 00:39:34,780
than the hockey mask,

828
00:39:34,819 --> 00:39:36,582
which of course
is now iconic.

829
00:39:36,621 --> 00:39:39,749
Brooker: I didn't get any direction
from Steve Miner at all.

830
00:39:39,791 --> 00:39:42,885
He actually came to me and said,
"You're just a mindless killer.

831
00:39:42,927 --> 00:39:46,021
You're like
the living version of 'Jaws." '

832
00:39:46,064 --> 00:39:48,328
I used to have to go in
and do about six,

833
00:39:48,366 --> 00:39:50,027
sometimes seven hours
of makeup.

834
00:39:50,068 --> 00:39:53,560
And it was 11 different appliances

835
00:39:53,604 --> 00:39:55,367
that they glued to my face.

836
00:39:55,406 --> 00:39:57,840
The bad part about it was
that as soon as they'd finished,

837
00:39:57,875 --> 00:40:00,343
it was usually lunchtime
and I couldn't eat.

838
00:40:00,378 --> 00:40:04,109
So they used to give me
Tiger's Milk through a straw.

839
00:40:04,148 --> 00:40:07,174
Judie Aronson: Jason in our film
was played by Ted White.

840
00:40:07,218 --> 00:40:10,517
And his way
of keeping the character

841
00:40:10,555 --> 00:40:13,115
was kind of separating himself
from everybody else.

842
00:40:13,157 --> 00:40:16,126
I don't remember really him having
a conversation with anybody.

843
00:40:16,160 --> 00:40:18,060
I actually turned it down
to begin with,

844
00:40:18,096 --> 00:40:20,587
and later on I did accept it.

845
00:40:20,631 --> 00:40:24,567
After I accepted it, I did go down
and rent two of the "Jasons,"

846
00:40:24,602 --> 00:40:26,797
and I watched Jason itself,

847
00:40:26,838 --> 00:40:28,931
how he moved and so forth.

848
00:40:28,973 --> 00:40:31,942
And I felt I'd like to play him
a little bit different.

849
00:40:31,976 --> 00:40:34,206
I'd like for him
to move a little bit different.

850
00:40:34,245 --> 00:40:36,645
Another way of doing it
would be the fast move,

851
00:40:36,681 --> 00:40:38,808
to move faster,
and that's how I portrayed him.

852
00:40:38,850 --> 00:40:41,284
That's what I wanted to do
with him.

853
00:40:41,319 --> 00:40:44,083
Even when I was in full costume,
makeup, everything,

854
00:40:44,122 --> 00:40:46,556
I stayed away
from the cast completely.

855
00:40:46,591 --> 00:40:48,821
I'd sit by myself on the set.

856
00:40:48,860 --> 00:40:50,691
I just stayed away
from everybody.

857
00:40:50,728 --> 00:40:53,128
And I tried to keep in character
as much as possible.

858
00:40:53,164 --> 00:40:55,189
I liked the mystique

859
00:40:55,233 --> 00:40:57,258
of being by myself,

860
00:40:57,301 --> 00:40:59,667
not being close to anybody.

861
00:40:59,704 --> 00:41:01,899
The scene upstairs where
they hit me over the head

862
00:41:01,939 --> 00:41:04,430
with a television set,

863
00:41:04,475 --> 00:41:07,911
little did I know that that
TV set was gonna stay on my head.

864
00:41:07,945 --> 00:41:10,641
I had no idea where I was.
I couldn't see out of that thing.

865
00:41:10,681 --> 00:41:13,548
It was just a hand feeling
for the stairway.

866
00:41:13,584 --> 00:41:16,212
You know, I was offered
the fifth one and sixth one.

867
00:41:16,254 --> 00:41:19,052
I could have done either one of them
and I turned 'em down.

868
00:41:19,090 --> 00:41:21,581
I'm sorry now
that I did turn them down.

869
00:41:21,626 --> 00:41:25,187
Morga: In "5," I actually
played an impostor of Jason,

870
00:41:25,229 --> 00:41:28,221
and I did have a couple moments
where I did

871
00:41:28,266 --> 00:41:30,097
play the apparition

872
00:41:30,134 --> 00:41:32,659
of Jason himself,

873
00:41:32,703 --> 00:41:36,298
where those were supposedly
different Jason characters.

874
00:41:36,340 --> 00:41:39,036
I just played Jason
through the whole movie.

875
00:41:39,076 --> 00:41:42,045
In the film, obviously,
they had to distinguish in some way

876
00:41:42,079 --> 00:41:45,674
so they used the blue
for the marks on the mask

877
00:41:45,716 --> 00:41:49,015
for the impostor Jason,
where when I did the actual Jason

878
00:41:49,053 --> 00:41:51,044
I was wearing the real mask

879
00:41:51,088 --> 00:41:53,079
with the red marks on it.

880
00:41:53,124 --> 00:41:56,924
The makeup with this particular
character wasn't too intense.

881
00:41:56,961 --> 00:41:59,259
The Jason character, though,

882
00:41:59,297 --> 00:42:02,232
was a pullover mask
with the face cut out.

883
00:42:02,266 --> 00:42:04,234
All they had to do
was darken my eyes

884
00:42:04,268 --> 00:42:05,997
and then put the hockey mask
over it.

885
00:42:06,037 --> 00:42:08,870
We never talked about this.
It's really not in the script.

886
00:42:08,906 --> 00:42:11,568
Any motivation...
there isn't any.

887
00:42:11,609 --> 00:42:15,545
So I felt Roy was a little disturbed
to begin with.

888
00:42:15,580 --> 00:42:18,515
The first time I put on
the green jumpsuit

889
00:42:18,549 --> 00:42:20,380
and the boots

890
00:42:20,418 --> 00:42:24,218
and I zipped them up,
I looked at myself in the mirror

891
00:42:24,255 --> 00:42:26,553
and I thought, "Is this me?"

892
00:42:26,591 --> 00:42:29,355
Bartalos:
One of the exciting things for me

893
00:42:29,393 --> 00:42:32,123
was the creation of Jason's mask.

894
00:42:32,163 --> 00:42:34,427
So we took a hockey mask

895
00:42:34,465 --> 00:42:36,695
and kind of customized it.

896
00:42:36,734 --> 00:42:38,964
We basically redesigned

897
00:42:39,003 --> 00:42:40,470
some of the ventilation holes.

898
00:42:40,504 --> 00:42:44,440
We created basically
a new positive.

899
00:42:44,475 --> 00:42:46,875
From the positive, we made
a big block rubber mold

900
00:42:46,911 --> 00:42:48,936
and from that,
created what's called a buck,

901
00:42:48,980 --> 00:42:51,710
a heavy-duty cement wedge that

902
00:42:51,749 --> 00:42:54,445
on the top
of it has the veneer

903
00:42:54,485 --> 00:42:55,975
of the hockey mask

904
00:42:56,020 --> 00:42:59,080
At that point,
using a real heavy duty plastic,

905
00:42:59,123 --> 00:43:01,091
we did what's called
vacuforming.

906
00:43:01,125 --> 00:43:02,786
The vacuforming draws apart

907
00:43:02,827 --> 00:43:05,227
and we pull it out and bang,

908
00:43:05,263 --> 00:43:07,390
we get Jason's mask.

909
00:43:07,431 --> 00:43:10,992
C.J. Graham: When we portrayed it,
he got stronger.

910
00:43:11,035 --> 00:43:14,801
Every opportunity
of a fight scene or a kill

911
00:43:14,839 --> 00:43:18,240
enhanced his knowledge
of killing or his strength.

912
00:43:18,276 --> 00:43:21,609
Every time he was shot and put down,
he came back stronger the next time.

913
00:43:25,683 --> 00:43:28,277
You know, Tom was very adamant.
He did not want a machine on stage.

914
00:43:28,319 --> 00:43:30,549
When you were on set,
he wanted to make sure

915
00:43:30,588 --> 00:43:32,613
there was some human contact

916
00:43:32,657 --> 00:43:34,682
and people could relate to it.

917
00:43:34,725 --> 00:43:37,717
Jason just is indestructible.
When you put the costume on,

918
00:43:37,762 --> 00:43:40,959
you really project it, and the
projection had to be through the body...

919
00:43:40,998 --> 00:43:44,490
100% through the body.
Just a simplistic little movement

920
00:43:44,535 --> 00:43:46,127
would create fear.

921
00:43:46,170 --> 00:43:48,195
As soon as the mask
comes down,

922
00:43:48,239 --> 00:43:50,366
it's very simple
to get into the character.

923
00:43:50,408 --> 00:43:52,899
Nice thing about it
is you get to kill 17, 18 people,

924
00:43:52,944 --> 00:43:54,536
you don't go to prison.

925
00:43:58,282 --> 00:44:01,046
Buechler:
Every scar, every rip, every tear

926
00:44:01,085 --> 00:44:02,950
that Jason ever had was

927
00:44:02,987 --> 00:44:06,889
in the Jason
that we created for "Part VII."

928
00:44:06,924 --> 00:44:10,223
As far as playing the character,
I wanted to just do what felt natural.

929
00:44:10,261 --> 00:44:13,162
My goal was
to just add some more life

930
00:44:13,197 --> 00:44:16,724
to the character,
even though he is kind of a zombie.

931
00:44:16,767 --> 00:44:19,930
People ask me, " Why does
the makeup change so much

932
00:44:19,971 --> 00:44:23,304
from movie to movie? The hockey mask
changes and everything else."

933
00:44:23,341 --> 00:44:26,174
Basically, it's because it's
a different makeup-effects person

934
00:44:26,210 --> 00:44:28,041
who designs it.

935
00:44:28,079 --> 00:44:30,240
The first movie I did,
"Part VII,"

936
00:44:30,281 --> 00:44:32,647
the makeup was real extensive,
many pieces.

937
00:44:32,683 --> 00:44:36,141
It took about three
and a half hours a day.

938
00:44:36,187 --> 00:44:39,281
It was hard to work in,
but fantastic makeup.

939
00:44:40,391 --> 00:44:42,586
ber Jason...
it was an entire

940
00:44:42,626 --> 00:44:45,060
one-piece suit

941
00:44:45,096 --> 00:44:48,361
that did have a zipper
in the back, but very well concealed.

942
00:44:48,399 --> 00:44:51,459
On the suit,
it limited my motion a lot

943
00:44:51,502 --> 00:44:53,970
with the arm and the leg

944
00:44:54,005 --> 00:44:55,870
that had the metallic pieces.

945
00:44:55,906 --> 00:44:59,364
I still love the design
of that ber Jason mask.

946
00:44:59,410 --> 00:45:01,878
He brought a lot to the role.

947
00:45:01,912 --> 00:45:05,848
No matter who directed him,
no matter what movie he was in,

948
00:45:05,883 --> 00:45:09,478
you could tell Kane's Jason
from other people's Jason.

949
00:45:09,520 --> 00:45:12,921
Having Kane Hodder
play Jason four times

950
00:45:12,957 --> 00:45:15,687
really established him
as Jason.

951
00:45:15,726 --> 00:45:19,093
I think stepping into it,
I was a little leery,

952
00:45:19,130 --> 00:45:22,156
because a lot of the feedback
the fans were putting out there

953
00:45:22,199 --> 00:45:24,167
was negative, I think,
in the beginning.

954
00:45:24,201 --> 00:45:26,465
But then when the movie
came out,

955
00:45:26,504 --> 00:45:28,301
it became very very positive.

956
00:45:28,339 --> 00:45:31,035
They were big shoes,
but I'm a big guy.

957
00:45:31,075 --> 00:45:33,441
I remember the first day
he showed up on the set,

958
00:45:33,477 --> 00:45:36,139
the first night we shot him,
and I turned around,

959
00:45:36,180 --> 00:45:38,011
and there he was in full glory.

960
00:45:38,049 --> 00:45:40,711
I mean, his boots were
like this thick,

961
00:45:40,751 --> 00:45:43,811
and then you put on
everything else that he's wearing

962
00:45:43,854 --> 00:45:45,719
and he was 6'8 ".

963
00:45:45,756 --> 00:45:48,725
I'm not kidding you,
he scared the hell out of me.

964
00:45:48,759 --> 00:45:50,920
My portrayal of Jason

965
00:45:50,961 --> 00:45:53,828
showed another side
that you don't normally get to see.

966
00:45:53,864 --> 00:45:56,355
In "Freddy vs. Jason,"
you see him actually interact

967
00:45:56,400 --> 00:46:00,166
with his mother,
and you see him confronted by fears.

968
00:46:00,204 --> 00:46:02,331
I just went back
to my childhood,

969
00:46:02,373 --> 00:46:04,933
and I think I thought
a lot about Frankenstein...

970
00:46:04,975 --> 00:46:07,341
not really alive,
but not really dead.

971
00:46:07,378 --> 00:46:10,245
Even if you look at the movements,
the walk and stuff like that,

972
00:46:10,281 --> 00:46:12,875
I think I used a little bit
of Frankenstein.

973
00:46:12,917 --> 00:46:16,011
Even though people think
he just kind of stands there

974
00:46:16,053 --> 00:46:17,816
and lumbers along
with his machete,

975
00:46:17,855 --> 00:46:20,187
you have to feel
that there's a physical force

976
00:46:20,224 --> 00:46:24,217
that could actually be as evil
and as powerful as he is.

977
00:46:28,699 --> 00:46:30,997
Ew! Sorry, buddy.

978
00:46:31,035 --> 00:46:33,663
I hope it was over quickly.

979
00:46:33,704 --> 00:46:35,137
The truth is,
like this guy,

980
00:46:35,172 --> 00:46:37,299
most people don't survive
their encounter

981
00:46:37,341 --> 00:46:39,536
with our murderous mongoloid.

982
00:46:39,577 --> 00:46:42,842
Still, there have been a few
that gave Jason quite a headache.

983
00:46:42,880 --> 00:46:46,111
You know, the people that insist
on not going down without a fight.

984
00:46:46,150 --> 00:46:47,811
It's a small group,

985
00:46:47,852 --> 00:46:51,515
but they certainly gave Jason
a big run for his money.

986
00:46:51,555 --> 00:46:53,819
Or his machete.

987
00:46:53,858 --> 00:46:56,793
So whether it's Alice or it's Ginny
or it's Chris or any of these girls

988
00:46:56,827 --> 00:46:59,955
who make it to the end, they usually
have some common characteristics.

989
00:46:59,997 --> 00:47:02,227
The most important
is their chastity,

990
00:47:02,266 --> 00:47:03,756
their purity.

991
00:47:03,801 --> 00:47:06,895
They're generally not there
to just party.

992
00:47:06,937 --> 00:47:08,996
And as a result,
they get rewarded

993
00:47:09,039 --> 00:47:11,030
by being able
to live through it.

994
00:47:11,075 --> 00:47:13,839
It was usually the outcast.
It was usually the good girl,

995
00:47:13,878 --> 00:47:16,278
the one who didn't smoke pot,
who didn't have premarital sex.

996
00:47:16,313 --> 00:47:18,372
She was always the one
who was able to take him on.

997
00:47:18,415 --> 00:47:21,145
And I think that goes back
to the most primitive storytelling

998
00:47:21,185 --> 00:47:22,652
of just good versus evil.

999
00:47:22,686 --> 00:47:25,985
The archetypes for them are
the innocent girl next door.

1000
00:47:26,023 --> 00:47:27,923
I never felt like a victim.

1001
00:47:27,958 --> 00:47:30,483
As a matter of fact,
I felt very empowered by the role.

1002
00:47:30,528 --> 00:47:33,827
The women were stronger
in this film than the guys were.

1003
00:47:33,864 --> 00:47:37,391
She's a typical, regular gal.

1004
00:47:37,434 --> 00:47:39,561
She's like any teenager

1005
00:47:39,603 --> 00:47:42,538
or young adult trying

1006
00:47:42,573 --> 00:47:44,837
to figure out what they
wanna do with their life.

1007
00:47:44,875 --> 00:47:47,343
She didn't run with the pack

1008
00:47:47,378 --> 00:47:50,040
and she was different.

1009
00:47:50,080 --> 00:47:52,446
But that didn't mean
she was virtuous.

1010
00:47:52,483 --> 00:47:55,646
It just meant she thought things
through differently.

1011
00:47:57,988 --> 00:48:00,422
I would love the opportunity
to come back.

1012
00:48:00,457 --> 00:48:02,425
It's so much more satisfying

1013
00:48:02,459 --> 00:48:04,120
to watch a woman

1014
00:48:04,161 --> 00:48:07,130
destroy this tremendous evil.

1015
00:48:07,164 --> 00:48:11,032
Amy Steel, she was just so adorable.
She was so girl-next-doorish.

1016
00:48:11,068 --> 00:48:14,970
She would probably be
my all-time favorite "Friday" girl.

1017
00:48:15,005 --> 00:48:17,098
To know that I did one
of these films

1018
00:48:17,141 --> 00:48:20,201
where they get all these women in
that are so vulnerable

1019
00:48:20,244 --> 00:48:23,042
and to be the one that
people think was strong

1020
00:48:23,080 --> 00:48:25,605
and intelligent is just...
it feels good.

1021
00:48:25,649 --> 00:48:27,617
Ginny was written

1022
00:48:27,651 --> 00:48:29,949
in a more multidimensional
kind of way.

1023
00:48:29,987 --> 00:48:33,479
And there was something a little bit
separate about her than everybody.

1024
00:48:33,524 --> 00:48:36,152
She didn't need a group
of people around her.

1025
00:48:36,193 --> 00:48:39,219
She was strong enough
to stand on her own.

1026
00:48:39,263 --> 00:48:41,231
She wanted to figure it out.

1027
00:48:41,265 --> 00:48:43,165
Well, what would it be like today?

1028
00:48:43,200 --> 00:48:46,135
Some kind of
out-of-control psychopath?

1029
00:48:46,170 --> 00:48:48,934
A frightened retard?

1030
00:48:48,973 --> 00:48:50,770
A child trapped
in a man's body?

1031
00:48:50,808 --> 00:48:54,005
I think my favorite personally
was Lar Park-Lincoln in "Part VII."

1032
00:48:54,044 --> 00:48:56,535
Just the ability
to come in with the mind

1033
00:48:56,580 --> 00:49:00,448
and to manipulate Jason like she did...
I mean, she was equal.

1034
00:49:00,484 --> 00:49:03,647
Roday: The genius convention
of adding a character

1035
00:49:03,687 --> 00:49:05,678
with telekinesis

1036
00:49:05,723 --> 00:49:08,157
to give Jason
a new sort of foil

1037
00:49:08,192 --> 00:49:10,285
in the final battle
was pretty fantastic.

1038
00:49:14,965 --> 00:49:17,729
One thing that I didn't want
to do is I didn't want

1039
00:49:17,768 --> 00:49:21,727
to play a psychic, or someone
who felt they had telekinetic abilities,

1040
00:49:21,772 --> 00:49:24,263
like they were someone
going into a stroke

1041
00:49:24,308 --> 00:49:27,368
and doing some
cartoonish version

1042
00:49:27,411 --> 00:49:30,608
of what
she was dealing with.

1043
00:49:30,648 --> 00:49:32,912
Lar Park-Lincoln as Tina,
she's classic.

1044
00:49:32,950 --> 00:49:35,851
It was a different take
on the story.

1045
00:49:35,886 --> 00:49:38,150
That character gave it
a great brawl.

1046
00:49:38,188 --> 00:49:41,680
Park-Lincoln: She didn't back down.
She never really ran from him.

1047
00:49:41,725 --> 00:49:44,159
She chased him.
And we had that great street scene

1048
00:49:44,194 --> 00:49:46,924
where she goes right up
to him... I love the twigs

1049
00:49:46,964 --> 00:49:48,295
coming around his legs

1050
00:49:48,332 --> 00:49:51,790
and taking him down
that way.

1051
00:49:51,835 --> 00:49:53,632
The most worthy opponents
of Jason

1052
00:49:53,671 --> 00:49:57,232
from the movies that I did...
certainly Tina has to be there,

1053
00:49:57,274 --> 00:50:00,038
because she created
the most damage

1054
00:50:00,077 --> 00:50:02,307
to Jason and survived.

1055
00:50:02,346 --> 00:50:05,782
They also started a trend where like
the surviving girl's "love interest"

1056
00:50:05,816 --> 00:50:07,716
started making it through
as well.

1057
00:50:07,751 --> 00:50:10,481
I'm honored that I was a survivor.

1058
00:50:12,022 --> 00:50:13,649
If Jason wanted
to bring it on again,

1059
00:50:13,691 --> 00:50:15,556
I'd come back.

1060
00:50:15,592 --> 00:50:17,219
I would love
to tackle her again.

1061
00:50:17,261 --> 00:50:20,924
Although I think I would do it
with better hair serum.

1062
00:50:20,964 --> 00:50:23,057
So my hair
wouldn't be as frizzy

1063
00:50:23,100 --> 00:50:25,330
as it was throughout
the entire shooting of that film.

1064
00:50:25,369 --> 00:50:27,963
I think of the whole series,
I think Tommy Jarvis is probably one

1065
00:50:28,005 --> 00:50:29,768
of Jason's biggest adversaries.

1066
00:50:29,807 --> 00:50:33,334
Jason, don't you remember?

1067
00:50:33,377 --> 00:50:35,845
Remember, Jason?

1068
00:50:38,248 --> 00:50:40,273
Zito:
Tommy's an outsider, like Jason.

1069
00:50:40,317 --> 00:50:42,217
Tommy's a kid
that doesn't fit in.

1070
00:50:42,252 --> 00:50:44,880
So there is a relationship
between Tommy and Jason

1071
00:50:44,922 --> 00:50:47,914
when Tommy takes on
the persona and impersonates him

1072
00:50:47,958 --> 00:50:51,121
as a weapon to undo him.

1073
00:50:52,996 --> 00:50:55,430
I would love to have gone up
against Corey Feldman

1074
00:50:55,466 --> 00:50:59,425
just 'cause I'd like
to squeeze his head until it pops.

1075
00:50:59,470 --> 00:51:01,597
Tommy had a very unique
relationship to Jason

1076
00:51:01,638 --> 00:51:03,868
because at least at the end
of "Part 5," he actually

1077
00:51:03,907 --> 00:51:06,239
looks like he will become
the next Jason.

1078
00:51:06,276 --> 00:51:08,938
In "Part 4," which Corey Feldman
played so beautifully,

1079
00:51:08,979 --> 00:51:11,209
he ends up
in an insane asylum.

1080
00:51:11,248 --> 00:51:14,149
Is he monster or victim?
Well, he's a little bit of both.

1081
00:51:16,620 --> 00:51:18,952
He just wants to kill everybody.

1082
00:51:18,989 --> 00:51:21,617
He didn't get me though.
I ran him over with a tractor...

1083
00:51:21,658 --> 00:51:24,149
one of the very few brothers
that survived

1084
00:51:24,194 --> 00:51:26,059
the "Friday the 13th" series,
by the way.

1085
00:51:26,096 --> 00:51:27,757
They wanted
to kill me off in "Part VI,"

1086
00:51:27,798 --> 00:51:30,631
but we said,
"Nope, not doing that to us."

1087
00:51:30,667 --> 00:51:32,134
(screams)

1088
00:51:32,169 --> 00:51:35,866
John LeMay's character...
another good one

1089
00:51:35,906 --> 00:51:37,498
because we had
a hell of a fight.

1090
00:51:37,541 --> 00:51:39,008
I did put up
a pretty good fight.

1091
00:51:39,042 --> 00:51:41,010
The electricity's going off
everywhere,

1092
00:51:41,044 --> 00:51:44,104
and I'm just breathing heavy
and sweating a lot

1093
00:51:44,148 --> 00:51:46,844
and smacking the hell out
of him. It was fun,

1094
00:51:46,884 --> 00:51:50,115
but surviving Jason is an honor.

1095
00:51:50,154 --> 00:51:53,612
In my obituary,
it'll say " John survived Jason,

1096
00:51:53,657 --> 00:51:55,852
but could not survive life."

1097
00:51:55,893 --> 00:51:58,885
Daggett: Rennie had
a special connection to Jason

1098
00:51:58,929 --> 00:52:02,160
because I think her evil uncle

1099
00:52:02,199 --> 00:52:05,134
was trying to teach her how
to swim when she was a little girl.

1100
00:52:05,169 --> 00:52:07,763
Peter Mark Richman:
I tossed her in the water,

1101
00:52:07,805 --> 00:52:11,104
which was a not-very-nice thing
to do for an uncle.

1102
00:52:11,141 --> 00:52:14,508
And she had
an inordinate fear

1103
00:52:14,545 --> 00:52:16,342
of drowning.

1104
00:52:16,380 --> 00:52:20,111
And she saw Jason
under the water.

1105
00:52:20,150 --> 00:52:21,640
(screaming)

1106
00:52:23,887 --> 00:52:26,685
I felt very empowered
playing the part, especially at the end

1107
00:52:26,723 --> 00:52:30,090
when I was the only one surviving
and there we were in the sewers.

1108
00:52:30,127 --> 00:52:32,618
And I felt like,

1109
00:52:32,663 --> 00:52:35,188
"All right,
this is a nice, tough,

1110
00:52:35,232 --> 00:52:38,167
accurate portrayal
of a girl's strength."

1111
00:52:38,202 --> 00:52:39,692
You didn't get me in the lake,

1112
00:52:39,736 --> 00:52:42,364
and you're not
gonna get me now!

1113
00:52:44,942 --> 00:52:47,843
I would probably go back
and do another "Friday the 13th."

1114
00:52:47,878 --> 00:52:51,370
If nothing else,
then just to make my boys happy.

1115
00:52:51,415 --> 00:52:53,280
Women in "Friday the 13th" movies

1116
00:52:53,317 --> 00:52:56,650
are always strong.
You know, they're strong characters.

1117
00:52:56,687 --> 00:52:58,314
And we wanted
to be true to that.

1118
00:52:58,355 --> 00:53:01,586
So Todd and I came up
with this idea of this robot

1119
00:53:01,625 --> 00:53:04,856
and making the robot female.

1120
00:53:04,895 --> 00:53:07,022
One of the most delightful things
about her

1121
00:53:07,064 --> 00:53:09,498
is like just unstoppable,
unflappable.

1122
00:53:09,533 --> 00:53:12,627
I feel very privileged in that
I got to survive that movie.

1123
00:53:12,669 --> 00:53:15,695
Even though he knocked
my block off and I was a head...

1124
00:53:15,739 --> 00:53:17,138
I was a talking head

1125
00:53:17,174 --> 00:53:20,075
for, I think, the last third
of the movie...

1126
00:53:20,110 --> 00:53:23,045
I feel like one
of the lucky ones.

1127
00:53:24,114 --> 00:53:26,548
I think most of the people
that have survived

1128
00:53:26,583 --> 00:53:29,450
have been women
because all of us directors

1129
00:53:29,486 --> 00:53:31,454
have a tremendous
amount of guilt

1130
00:53:31,488 --> 00:53:33,683
for what we've done
to all of these poor girls

1131
00:53:33,724 --> 00:53:35,385
in the movies.

1132
00:53:35,425 --> 00:53:38,622
I do think that the heroines
have a strength that's there,

1133
00:53:38,662 --> 00:53:40,926
but a real vulnerability

1134
00:53:40,964 --> 00:53:42,932
that attracts people.

1135
00:53:42,966 --> 00:53:46,458
People wanna love you
and they wanna cheer for you.

1136
00:53:46,503 --> 00:53:48,368
Steel:
If they were to ask me

1137
00:53:48,405 --> 00:53:52,171
to do sort of
the "Friday the 13th" survivors...

1138
00:53:52,209 --> 00:53:55,701
gonna take on Jason...
would I do it?

1139
00:53:55,746 --> 00:53:57,077
Hell yeah!

1140
00:53:57,114 --> 00:53:58,706
Wouldn't it be great

1141
00:53:58,749 --> 00:54:02,412
if the strong women
of the series came back

1142
00:54:02,452 --> 00:54:04,613
and took him on?

1143
00:54:04,655 --> 00:54:08,489
It would be great... so maybe
Adrienne and Lar and myself.

1144
00:54:08,525 --> 00:54:11,085
I think that it would be very
interesting if you had a triad

1145
00:54:11,128 --> 00:54:14,256
of the girls,
where you would have the powers,

1146
00:54:14,298 --> 00:54:17,563
an extremely strong one
and just a ballsy character.

1147
00:54:17,601 --> 00:54:21,128
It would be a dream movie for the fans.
And I think we could still pull it off.

1148
00:54:21,171 --> 00:54:22,968
We still have a couple
of good years in us.

1149
00:54:23,006 --> 00:54:26,635
Jason? Where's Jason?!

1150
00:54:26,677 --> 00:54:28,941
We took care of him.

1151
00:54:28,979 --> 00:54:32,278
(siren wails)

1152
00:54:32,449 --> 00:54:34,178
(whimpers)

1153
00:54:34,251 --> 00:54:36,776
Please please
please, help me.

1154
00:54:38,789 --> 00:54:40,848
(girl screaming)

1155
00:54:49,499 --> 00:54:53,128
Yeah, bad luck
sure can be bloody.

1156
00:54:53,170 --> 00:54:56,662
It's not just the victims
on the screen that run into problems.

1157
00:54:56,707 --> 00:55:00,199
Over the past 30 years
there have been troublesome times

1158
00:55:00,243 --> 00:55:03,576
for the "Friday the 13th"
filmmakers as well.

1159
00:55:03,614 --> 00:55:05,912
Many had nothing
whatsoever to do

1160
00:55:05,949 --> 00:55:08,713
with our hockey-masked friend.

1161
00:55:08,752 --> 00:55:12,153
Paul?
(screaming)

1162
00:55:14,591 --> 00:55:18,118
Shooting my death scene
was a bit of a challenge.

1163
00:55:18,161 --> 00:55:20,595
That's where
the horror part came

1164
00:55:20,631 --> 00:55:23,498
into the filming with me.

1165
00:55:23,533 --> 00:55:27,162
From here down,
I was in the water.

1166
00:55:27,204 --> 00:55:29,035
There were points
where I just felt

1167
00:55:29,072 --> 00:55:31,302
like I couldn't go on anymore.

1168
00:55:31,341 --> 00:55:35,300
It was either 22 or 23.
It was very very cold

1169
00:55:35,345 --> 00:55:38,143
and she had a bikini on
and she was freezing.

1170
00:55:38,181 --> 00:55:40,308
She was so cold
her teeth were chattering,

1171
00:55:40,350 --> 00:55:42,079
and this girl
was actually turning blue.

1172
00:55:42,119 --> 00:55:44,417
Aronson:
Ted White stood up for me

1173
00:55:44,454 --> 00:55:46,615
and demanded that we

1174
00:55:46,657 --> 00:55:49,091
get the shot now or else.

1175
00:55:49,126 --> 00:55:52,926
And it turns out that I had
gotten hypothermia,

1176
00:55:52,963 --> 00:55:54,430
and I was quite sick

1177
00:55:54,464 --> 00:55:57,592
for several days after that.

1178
00:55:57,634 --> 00:56:01,536
LeMay: A whole day spent
filming the end of the movie

1179
00:56:01,571 --> 00:56:03,505
where Jason's getting
sucked into the earth

1180
00:56:03,540 --> 00:56:05,303
and trying to drag me down
with him.

1181
00:56:05,342 --> 00:56:09,039
On the soundstage, they'd pretty
much created this large sandbox

1182
00:56:09,079 --> 00:56:11,274
with a hole in it,
which Jason would pop up,

1183
00:56:11,314 --> 00:56:14,181
grab me by the leg
and keep pulling me down.

1184
00:56:14,217 --> 00:56:18,085
And for some reason
that sequence took a half a day

1185
00:56:18,121 --> 00:56:20,248
with me screaming
at the top of my lungs

1186
00:56:20,290 --> 00:56:21,689
and just wearing my body out.

1187
00:56:21,725 --> 00:56:24,694
I thought every shot was gonna
be the last dang one, you know?

1188
00:56:24,728 --> 00:56:26,889
I thought it was it.
"We got this one, baby."

1189
00:56:26,930 --> 00:56:30,627
I don't think I've ever
been so exhausted in my life.

1190
00:56:30,667 --> 00:56:33,727
Man: Now, dirt demons,
everything up, moving.

1191
00:56:33,770 --> 00:56:36,068
Al Magliochetti:
The visual-effects climax,

1192
00:56:36,106 --> 00:56:39,200
all these demons came up
from below the ground

1193
00:56:39,242 --> 00:56:43,110
and started grabbing Jason
and trying to pull him down into hell.

1194
00:56:43,146 --> 00:56:46,274
And KNB had a very elaborate
sequence designed for that,

1195
00:56:46,316 --> 00:56:49,410
with all kinds of puppets.
And we had a very elaborate miniature...

1196
00:56:49,453 --> 00:56:52,388
which wound up not being used
because of technical problems...

1197
00:56:52,422 --> 00:56:54,390
that actually grabbed Jason

1198
00:56:54,424 --> 00:56:57,086
and started dragging him under.

1199
00:56:57,127 --> 00:56:59,789
Isn't that cool?
How many people get this going on?

1200
00:56:59,830 --> 00:57:02,424
On the final day of production

1201
00:57:02,466 --> 00:57:05,526
I got my action figure...

1202
00:57:05,569 --> 00:57:08,163
made by the hair
and makeup guys.

1203
00:57:08,205 --> 00:57:10,503
So this is my one-of-a-kind
action figure.

1204
00:57:10,540 --> 00:57:12,770
We shot the ending twice.

1205
00:57:12,809 --> 00:57:15,243
We actually did
another ending,

1206
00:57:15,278 --> 00:57:18,304
which most people
have never seen,

1207
00:57:18,348 --> 00:57:20,578
in which Dana Kimmell
comes up to the door

1208
00:57:20,617 --> 00:57:22,278
of the house in a dream,

1209
00:57:22,319 --> 00:57:24,287
and Jason comes
through the front door

1210
00:57:24,321 --> 00:57:25,811
and decapitates her.

1211
00:57:25,856 --> 00:57:28,484
This is the actual mask that
was done on my skin.

1212
00:57:28,525 --> 00:57:31,289
It's a little...

1213
00:57:31,328 --> 00:57:34,092
oh, here's a worm.

1214
00:57:34,131 --> 00:57:36,725
It's a little crumbly,
but it's split up the back

1215
00:57:36,767 --> 00:57:39,395
because as it was on my face
all the way around my neck...

1216
00:57:39,436 --> 00:57:40,835
I had a bald cap on...

1217
00:57:40,871 --> 00:57:43,772
they did the whole thing
right on my head.

1218
00:57:43,807 --> 00:57:46,742
And so to get me out of it,
they split it right up the back.

1219
00:57:46,777 --> 00:57:49,974
So it used to be something
like this, but...

1220
00:57:52,983 --> 00:57:56,384
Monoson:
My parents are away in the movie...

1221
00:57:56,419 --> 00:57:58,319
I had to be stoned.

1222
00:57:58,355 --> 00:58:00,983
And so I thought,
"Hmm, wouldn't that be interesting

1223
00:58:01,024 --> 00:58:03,219
to actually be stoned
on camera?"

1224
00:58:03,260 --> 00:58:06,559
So I go to my trailer
and I get stoned.

1225
00:58:06,596 --> 00:58:08,928
I'm a very paranoid
stoned person.

1226
00:58:08,965 --> 00:58:12,833
So it was the worst worst idea
I could have ever done.

1227
00:58:12,869 --> 00:58:14,837
And they knocked on my door
to go to the set.

1228
00:58:14,871 --> 00:58:17,499
I'm like, "What?!"
And they're like, "We're ready for you,"

1229
00:58:17,541 --> 00:58:20,032
and I'm like, "Okay."
(laughs)

1230
00:58:20,076 --> 00:58:22,044
So they take me
and I'm on the set,

1231
00:58:22,078 --> 00:58:25,070
and, actors,
don't get stoned and act.

1232
00:58:25,115 --> 00:58:27,640
It's absolutely the worst thing.

1233
00:58:27,684 --> 00:58:29,413
I was out of my mind.

1234
00:58:29,452 --> 00:58:31,545
Richman:
I do remember a scene

1235
00:58:31,588 --> 00:58:35,149
in my bedroom
where this girl comes on to me,

1236
00:58:35,192 --> 00:58:37,752
and I was getting
very keyed up,

1237
00:58:37,794 --> 00:58:39,227
turned on.

1238
00:58:39,262 --> 00:58:41,890
In the editing
they didn't show any of that.

1239
00:58:41,932 --> 00:58:43,490
And I was pissed off.

1240
00:58:43,533 --> 00:58:45,660
I was really...

1241
00:58:45,702 --> 00:58:47,761
having it affect me.

1242
00:58:47,804 --> 00:58:51,331
The MPAA really went after
the "Friday the 13th" films,

1243
00:58:51,374 --> 00:58:53,808
'cause they were asleep
when the first film was rated.

1244
00:58:53,844 --> 00:58:56,608
They kind of let it pass.
When the sequels came out,

1245
00:58:56,646 --> 00:59:00,241
and after all the criticism,
they had to be more stringent.

1246
00:59:00,283 --> 00:59:04,083
Probably the most heavily edited
was "Part VII."

1247
00:59:04,120 --> 00:59:07,521
The MPAA was just vicious
toward that film for some reason.

1248
00:59:07,557 --> 00:59:10,390
Ratings board raped my movie.

1249
00:59:10,427 --> 00:59:12,895
I equate horror

1250
00:59:12,929 --> 00:59:14,590
to telling a joke.

1251
00:59:14,631 --> 00:59:16,792
Everything's in the setup
and then the payoff

1252
00:59:16,833 --> 00:59:19,028
has gotta be,
"Whoa, that's great!"

1253
00:59:19,069 --> 00:59:21,469
We were telling the joke
and we weren't allowed

1254
00:59:21,504 --> 00:59:23,369
to give them the punchline.

1255
00:59:23,406 --> 00:59:25,465
So what you see

1256
00:59:25,508 --> 00:59:27,476
in the final cut of "Friday VII,"

1257
00:59:27,510 --> 00:59:30,946
which is not really my cut,
is a very watered-down version

1258
00:59:30,981 --> 00:59:33,040
of what we hoped it would be.

1259
00:59:33,083 --> 00:59:35,574
Rotten:
The MPAA was just responding

1260
00:59:35,619 --> 00:59:39,146
to a lot of parent advocate groups
that were coming out of the woodwork.

1261
00:59:39,189 --> 00:59:42,556
I mean, you had parents picketing
out in front of theaters

1262
00:59:42,592 --> 00:59:44,492
for certain films sometimes.

1263
00:59:44,527 --> 00:59:48,122
I think the MPAA gets crazy
when you combine sex and violence

1264
00:59:48,164 --> 00:59:51,099
at the same time, so I think that's
something you have to be careful about.

1265
00:59:51,134 --> 00:59:53,728
All the sequels
really went through the wringer

1266
00:59:53,770 --> 00:59:55,965
to secure R ratings.

1267
00:59:56,006 --> 00:59:58,770
Steinmann:
The MPAA,

1268
00:59:58,808 --> 01:00:02,437
after a lot heavy-duty fights,

1269
01:00:04,547 --> 01:00:08,142
insisted that we omit
47 seconds.

1270
01:00:08,184 --> 01:00:10,015
Almost every kill

1271
01:00:10,053 --> 01:00:13,022
was either off-screen

1272
01:00:13,056 --> 01:00:14,148
or minimized.

1273
01:00:14,190 --> 01:00:16,818
Ross: Tiffany Helm, there was a scene
that nobody knows about,

1274
01:00:16,860 --> 01:00:19,590
where she had her death scene.
I think they had to change it

1275
01:00:19,629 --> 01:00:22,223
because it would have
been rated X if they kept it.

1276
01:00:23,667 --> 01:00:26,261
Jason was gonna
go in for the kill.

1277
01:00:26,303 --> 01:00:28,635
Tiffany was gonna have
her legs up like this,

1278
01:00:28,672 --> 01:00:31,937
and he was just gonna go like...
couldn't show that.

1279
01:00:31,975 --> 01:00:35,536
Couldn't show that back then.
That was cut. Rated X.

1280
01:00:35,578 --> 01:00:37,569
X. Shoot it.

1281
01:00:39,950 --> 01:00:43,579
King: "Friday the 13th" was
the greatest experience for me,

1282
01:00:43,620 --> 01:00:45,713
and then slowly I realized

1283
01:00:45,755 --> 01:00:47,620
I had a stalker.

1284
01:00:47,657 --> 01:00:51,058
I had an ordeal with him
up close at one point,

1285
01:00:51,094 --> 01:00:53,654
which in itself
is a horror movie.

1286
01:00:55,065 --> 01:00:57,863
It's all okay now.
It's all good now.

1287
01:00:59,235 --> 01:01:01,760
And having
the three generations

1288
01:01:01,805 --> 01:01:05,263
of fans from
around the world that fly in

1289
01:01:05,308 --> 01:01:08,573
to wherever I am
at a city or a convention

1290
01:01:08,611 --> 01:01:11,341
that really talk to me
and care and tell me how much

1291
01:01:11,381 --> 01:01:13,474
it affected them
when they found out...

1292
01:01:13,516 --> 01:01:15,279
it's just a gift.

1293
01:01:15,318 --> 01:01:19,721
It's a beautiful thing and I don't
care how sappy it sounds.

1294
01:01:19,756 --> 01:01:22,725
I thank them.

1295
01:01:23,927 --> 01:01:26,418
Steel:
One of the scary moments on the set

1296
01:01:26,463 --> 01:01:28,693
was in Jason's lair

1297
01:01:28,732 --> 01:01:31,530
when I put the sweater on

1298
01:01:31,568 --> 01:01:33,160
and I talked to him
about Mother.

1299
01:01:33,203 --> 01:01:35,296
And he's supposed

1300
01:01:35,338 --> 01:01:37,670
to bring up this pickaxe.

1301
01:01:37,707 --> 01:01:39,766
So I got really anxious

1302
01:01:39,809 --> 01:01:42,437
and I brought the machete down.

1303
01:01:42,479 --> 01:01:44,777
She missed the pickaxe,

1304
01:01:44,814 --> 01:01:47,248
and she came down
on my finger.

1305
01:01:47,283 --> 01:01:49,751
Steel:
And he goes to the hospital...

1306
01:01:49,786 --> 01:01:52,550
I think he had the machete
through his chest or something

1307
01:01:52,589 --> 01:01:54,682
and walks into
the emergency room

1308
01:01:54,724 --> 01:01:56,783
and they're like, "Oh my God!"

1309
01:01:56,826 --> 01:01:59,386
Then he said, " No no,
it's just right here on my finger."

1310
01:01:59,429 --> 01:02:02,455
And I have 13 stitches
in this finger.

1311
01:02:02,499 --> 01:02:05,093
It's right here.
This right here, it's 13 stitches.

1312
01:02:05,135 --> 01:02:07,467
And then he came back

1313
01:02:07,504 --> 01:02:09,665
and we started all over again.

1314
01:02:09,706 --> 01:02:13,665
We stayed at the camp. At one
of our first nights in the cabins...

1315
01:02:13,710 --> 01:02:16,110
I think it was John Furey
and Bill Randolph

1316
01:02:16,146 --> 01:02:17,943
and Russell Todd...

1317
01:02:17,981 --> 01:02:20,108
knew where I was staying.

1318
01:02:20,150 --> 01:02:22,175
And they went
to the screen windows

1319
01:02:22,218 --> 01:02:23,810
when it was really dark out

1320
01:02:23,853 --> 01:02:27,550
and they started scratching
on the screen windows.

1321
01:02:27,590 --> 01:02:30,787
I fainted.
I actually fainted

1322
01:02:30,827 --> 01:02:32,692
flat on the floor

1323
01:02:32,729 --> 01:02:35,562
'cause I just went... (gasps)
Boom!

1324
01:02:38,601 --> 01:02:41,229
(rock music playing)

1325
01:02:42,305 --> 01:02:44,170
Though the counselors
at Crystal Lake

1326
01:02:44,207 --> 01:02:47,404
worked very hard to keep
the rules of the camp clear,

1327
01:02:47,444 --> 01:02:50,470
the same can't be said
for the "Friday the 13th" films,

1328
01:02:50,513 --> 01:02:53,812
which have had more
than their share of ambiguities

1329
01:02:53,850 --> 01:02:55,579
and inconsistencies,

1330
01:02:55,618 --> 01:02:57,643
leaving the fans longing
for more.

1331
01:03:00,290 --> 01:03:02,121
Oh, no way, Becca.

1332
01:03:02,158 --> 01:03:05,559
- You so owe me a Wonderbra.
- (giggles)

1333
01:03:05,595 --> 01:03:07,654
Well, okay.

1334
01:03:07,697 --> 01:03:10,257
Strip Monopoly's
so much fun.

1335
01:03:10,300 --> 01:03:11,927
Oooh!

1336
01:03:15,038 --> 01:03:16,903
Camp Crystal Lake rocks.

1337
01:03:17,974 --> 01:03:19,908
One of the things
that the "Friday" series

1338
01:03:19,943 --> 01:03:21,968
never really took pride in
was continuity.

1339
01:03:22,011 --> 01:03:25,037
How could it be Friday the 13th
if "2," "III" and "4"

1340
01:03:25,081 --> 01:03:26,844
are within three or four days?

1341
01:03:26,883 --> 01:03:28,851
I don't think Monday the 16th

1342
01:03:28,885 --> 01:03:30,853
has quite the same ring to it.

1343
01:03:30,887 --> 01:03:32,855
Cohen:
People send me Jason timelines

1344
01:03:32,889 --> 01:03:35,983
and show me categorically
where I'm wrong about certain things,

1345
01:03:36,025 --> 01:03:38,619
and where the writer of "VI" was wrong,
or the writer of "III" was wrong.

1346
01:03:38,661 --> 01:03:42,062
And you know what, so what?
I just don't know.

1347
01:03:42,098 --> 01:03:44,658
King:
The fans have told me

1348
01:03:44,701 --> 01:03:47,192
at convention after convention

1349
01:03:47,237 --> 01:03:49,831
that they felt "ripped off"

1350
01:03:49,873 --> 01:03:52,364
about the way Alice died
in "Part 2."

1351
01:03:52,408 --> 01:03:55,809
She didn't even see him.
It's like it could have been anyone.

1352
01:03:55,845 --> 01:03:57,870
As far as I'm concerned,
it was somebody else.

1353
01:03:57,914 --> 01:04:01,179
If Jason is who I believe he is

1354
01:04:01,217 --> 01:04:03,412
and who I think the fans
think he is,

1355
01:04:03,453 --> 01:04:06,388
it's not like he can look
her number up in the phonebook.

1356
01:04:06,422 --> 01:04:09,050
It's not like she would be listed
in the phonebook.

1357
01:04:09,092 --> 01:04:10,855
She got away.
But in the second one

1358
01:04:10,894 --> 01:04:12,885
he comes to her apartment
and kills her?

1359
01:04:12,929 --> 01:04:15,727
Now what I want to know is
how did Jason get a plane ticket?

1360
01:04:15,765 --> 01:04:18,563
There was a "Friday the 13th"
TV series.

1361
01:04:18,601 --> 01:04:21,069
LeMay:
The only thing that the series

1362
01:04:21,104 --> 01:04:22,833
and the movies

1363
01:04:22,872 --> 01:04:24,339
had in common
was the title.

1364
01:04:24,374 --> 01:04:27,207
It turns out it was about
people trying

1365
01:04:27,243 --> 01:04:29,837
to retrieve cursed artifacts

1366
01:04:29,879 --> 01:04:31,437
from a pawnshop.

1367
01:04:31,481 --> 01:04:34,348
I think a lot of people who were
really big fans of the series

1368
01:04:34,384 --> 01:04:36,511
didn't like the fact
that they stole the name

1369
01:04:36,553 --> 01:04:39,852
and tried to sneak a fast one
past everybody.

1370
01:04:40,890 --> 01:04:42,687
So beginning with "Part III,"

1371
01:04:42,725 --> 01:04:45,193
when Jason finds the mask

1372
01:04:45,228 --> 01:04:47,628
that everyone identifies
with him,

1373
01:04:47,664 --> 01:04:49,962
there's been some debate
over the years about

1374
01:04:49,999 --> 01:04:51,591
how that happened.

1375
01:04:51,634 --> 01:04:54,364
And the one thing that
everybody likes to take credit for

1376
01:04:54,404 --> 01:04:57,567
is who put the hockey mask
on Jason.

1377
01:04:57,607 --> 01:05:00,269
One day we were doing
makeup tests

1378
01:05:00,310 --> 01:05:02,870
on "Friday the 13th Part III."

1379
01:05:02,912 --> 01:05:04,709
So just for the 3D concept,

1380
01:05:04,747 --> 01:05:07,648
I must admit, in modesty,

1381
01:05:07,684 --> 01:05:09,879
that I put the hockey mask
on Jason.

1382
01:05:09,919 --> 01:05:11,477
I don't care
what anybody says.

1383
01:05:11,521 --> 01:05:14,217
They weren't gonna use that bag again
based on what happened

1384
01:05:14,257 --> 01:05:16,885
to me with the burns.
They had to come up with another idea.

1385
01:05:16,926 --> 01:05:19,156
That's why they came up
with the hockey mask.

1386
01:05:19,195 --> 01:05:22,096
I believe it was Peter Schindler

1387
01:05:22,131 --> 01:05:26,033
and Marty Becker were
Detroit hockey fans.

1388
01:05:26,069 --> 01:05:28,970
And it was their idea
to come up with a hockey mask

1389
01:05:29,005 --> 01:05:30,939
to cover the face up.

1390
01:05:30,974 --> 01:05:33,033
Every time
kids come to my door

1391
01:05:33,076 --> 01:05:34,941
wearing
the Jason hockey mask,

1392
01:05:34,978 --> 01:05:38,436
I figure, " Wow, this is
another 50 I didn't get."

1393
01:05:38,481 --> 01:05:41,609
They're all still bickering
about it, but you heard it here...

1394
01:05:41,651 --> 01:05:43,346
mine.

1395
01:05:43,386 --> 01:05:46,287
Katz: The end of
"Friday the 13th Part 2" is still

1396
01:05:46,322 --> 01:05:49,155
one of the most confusing endings
of that series.

1397
01:05:49,192 --> 01:05:51,592
Probably easily the most,
other than the toxic-waste

1398
01:05:51,628 --> 01:05:53,493
version of teenaged Jason.

1399
01:05:53,529 --> 01:05:56,157
Paul! Where's Paul?

1400
01:05:56,199 --> 01:05:59,794
For me, it wasn't a dream.

1401
01:05:59,836 --> 01:06:01,997
Maybe that's one
of the good parts of the movie

1402
01:06:02,038 --> 01:06:04,268
is that you get to decide that
for yourself.

1403
01:06:04,307 --> 01:06:07,367
On "Freddy vs. Jason,"
they went a different direction

1404
01:06:07,410 --> 01:06:11,176
with casting Jason

1405
01:06:11,214 --> 01:06:13,546
and didn't cast Kane Hodder.

1406
01:06:13,583 --> 01:06:16,711
And I was really surprised.

1407
01:06:16,753 --> 01:06:20,553
I really wanted to use Kane
and then Ronnie Yu decided

1408
01:06:20,590 --> 01:06:23,218
that he really kind of
liked this other guy.

1409
01:06:23,259 --> 01:06:26,285
And he was directing
the movie and I said, "Fine."

1410
01:06:26,329 --> 01:06:29,924
It was a shame at some level
that Kane didn't get to do it.

1411
01:06:29,966 --> 01:06:32,958
About our clothes, I mean...

1412
01:06:33,002 --> 01:06:35,596
that's slightly the weirdest thing
about our roles,

1413
01:06:35,638 --> 01:06:37,731
which were supposed
to be these sexy girls

1414
01:06:37,774 --> 01:06:39,867
and we're dressed
in these ghastly clothes.

1415
01:06:39,909 --> 01:06:41,809
Camilla More:
What about our hair as well?

1416
01:06:41,844 --> 01:06:44,210
Our hair put up in sort
of little librarian buns.

1417
01:06:44,247 --> 01:06:45,578
I mean, hello.

1418
01:06:45,615 --> 01:06:49,016
And the pink puffy shirts
with the shoulder pads.

1419
01:06:49,052 --> 01:06:52,215
Lynch: It's kind of like
Springfield for " The Simpsons."

1420
01:06:52,255 --> 01:06:55,349
It's like, where is Crystal Lake?
It would be nice to find out someday

1421
01:06:55,391 --> 01:06:58,360
where is this Crystal Lake,
'cause I'd like to go there and swim.

1422
01:06:58,394 --> 01:07:02,194
I can definitively answer
the question of where is Crystal Lake.

1423
01:07:02,231 --> 01:07:05,962
Crystal Lake is in
Green Valley, New Jersey.

1424
01:07:06,002 --> 01:07:08,527
And the reason we know that
is because in "Part III,"

1425
01:07:08,571 --> 01:07:11,131
Shelly and Vera go
to a country store

1426
01:07:11,174 --> 01:07:13,335
and in the store,
you can see in the back,

1427
01:07:13,376 --> 01:07:17,039
it says " Welcome to Green Valley,
New Jersey." Case closed.

1428
01:07:17,080 --> 01:07:20,015
Katz: "Jason Takes Manhattan"...
outside of having one of the great

1429
01:07:20,049 --> 01:07:23,041
teaser posters of all time,
which of course was then discontinued,

1430
01:07:23,086 --> 01:07:25,077
ultimately, the "I Heart New York,"

1431
01:07:25,121 --> 01:07:27,214
that's actually something
that's trademarked

1432
01:07:27,256 --> 01:07:30,350
by probably, I'm guessing,
the tourism bureau, if memory serves,

1433
01:07:30,393 --> 01:07:33,885
and that's actually a very valuable
license to them, ultimately.

1434
01:07:35,665 --> 01:07:38,634
Crystal Lake has changed sizes.
Somehow the boat gets

1435
01:07:38,668 --> 01:07:41,831
from this tiny little lake
to the Atlantic Ocean

1436
01:07:41,871 --> 01:07:43,429
to New York.

1437
01:07:43,473 --> 01:07:45,771
The cruise ship wasn't really
in the lake.

1438
01:07:45,808 --> 01:07:48,868
The cruise ship was on the ocean.
In my mind, I had it justified,

1439
01:07:48,911 --> 01:07:51,471
because I've seen places where
you can go from a lake to the ocean.

1440
01:07:51,514 --> 01:07:53,675
And we ultimately just said,
"No, let's forget it.

1441
01:07:53,716 --> 01:07:56,116
People may get mad at us for that,
but let's go for it."

1442
01:07:56,152 --> 01:07:57,949
Body switching
in "Jason Goes to Hell,"

1443
01:07:57,987 --> 01:08:00,182
I think that was a terrible
terrible decision.

1444
01:08:00,223 --> 01:08:03,215
Roday:
The fact that Jason turned into a slug

1445
01:08:03,259 --> 01:08:07,218
in "Part 9"...unacceptable.

1446
01:08:07,263 --> 01:08:09,163
Gordon.

1447
01:08:12,068 --> 01:08:14,002
The most rational character
in the entire

1448
01:08:14,070 --> 01:08:16,300
"Friday the 13th" series
is the dog in "Part 4."

1449
01:08:16,339 --> 01:08:19,365
You don't know whether Jason grabbed
the dog and threw him out the window.

1450
01:08:19,409 --> 01:08:21,775
The dog sees Jason
and the next shot is the dog

1451
01:08:21,811 --> 01:08:23,745
apparently jumping
through the window.

1452
01:08:23,780 --> 01:08:26,578
There was a big fight over
whether we could kill the dog.

1453
01:08:26,616 --> 01:08:28,311
I think he jumped,
but I was hoping

1454
01:08:28,351 --> 01:08:30,114
some people will
think Jason did it.

1455
01:08:30,153 --> 01:08:33,452
Maybe Tina from "VII" telekinetically
yanked the dog out the window.

1456
01:08:41,464 --> 01:08:44,365
Well, he was bound
to catch up with her... sooner or later.

1457
01:08:44,400 --> 01:08:46,300
If there's one thing
that we've learned

1458
01:08:46,335 --> 01:08:49,202
it's escaping Jason
is a rarity.

1459
01:08:49,238 --> 01:08:51,638
Over the last three decades,
his reign of terror

1460
01:08:51,674 --> 01:08:54,404
has gone beyond
the silver screen.

1461
01:08:54,444 --> 01:08:56,241
In fact, it's clear that Jason

1462
01:08:56,279 --> 01:08:58,577
has done more
than take Manhattan.

1463
01:08:58,614 --> 01:09:00,673
In fact, I'd say
he's conquered the world.

1464
01:09:04,887 --> 01:09:06,149
(gears grind)

1465
01:09:06,189 --> 01:09:09,283
Oh! That had to hurt.

1466
01:09:09,325 --> 01:09:10,883
Interestingly enough,

1467
01:09:10,927 --> 01:09:14,886
Jason did manage
to infiltrate the pop culture

1468
01:09:14,931 --> 01:09:18,059
in a big big way.
And I think that all started

1469
01:09:18,100 --> 01:09:21,433
with "Part III" in 3D.

1470
01:09:21,471 --> 01:09:24,463
I have the home-theater glass set,

1471
01:09:24,507 --> 01:09:27,533
so you can see it and watch it
and people would walk into my house

1472
01:09:27,577 --> 01:09:29,602
and I have them on,
and be like, " Hey, what's up?

1473
01:09:29,645 --> 01:09:31,169
I'm watching
'Friday the 13th Part III." '

1474
01:09:31,214 --> 01:09:34,479
Graham: From a merchandising
perspective, it's huge.

1475
01:09:34,517 --> 01:09:36,712
I cannot believe
the branding of Jason.

1476
01:09:36,752 --> 01:09:39,118
He is no less marketable
than Ronald McDonald

1477
01:09:39,155 --> 01:09:40,918
or Mickey Mouse at this point.

1478
01:09:40,957 --> 01:09:43,016
Jason is making money.

1479
01:09:43,059 --> 01:09:46,119
I mean, does he get
a percentage of the sales?

1480
01:09:46,162 --> 01:09:47,720
I'm very curious.

1481
01:09:47,763 --> 01:09:50,231
Jason Voorhees has been
mass marketed over the years,

1482
01:09:50,266 --> 01:09:52,860
starting with this Nintendo game
back in the early '80s.

1483
01:09:52,902 --> 01:09:54,529
Adam Green:
That was the worst game ever.

1484
01:09:54,570 --> 01:09:57,300
All you did is run around the cabins. And
there'd be like nothing, nothing,

1485
01:09:57,340 --> 01:09:58,568
Jason's in here! I'm dead.

1486
01:09:58,608 --> 01:10:01,839
My name's James Rolfe.
I have an internet show...

1487
01:10:01,878 --> 01:10:03,345
"The Angry Video Game Nerd."

1488
01:10:03,379 --> 01:10:05,813
The "Friday the 13th" episode
made its debut

1489
01:10:05,848 --> 01:10:09,614
on Friday the 13th,
October 2006.

1490
01:10:09,652 --> 01:10:12,212
Uh-oh, he's coming. Whoa!

1491
01:10:12,255 --> 01:10:14,985
Well, he scared the shit out
of me and now he's fighting me

1492
01:10:15,024 --> 01:10:17,117
like in " Mike Tyson's
Punch-Out!!"

1493
01:10:17,159 --> 01:10:18,990
They've created a hero image

1494
01:10:19,028 --> 01:10:22,623
of an individual that's unstoppable.

1495
01:10:22,665 --> 01:10:24,189
He's this super slasher hero.

1496
01:10:24,233 --> 01:10:26,030
There's no rhyme or reason,
you know?

1497
01:10:26,068 --> 01:10:28,628
He's been on lunchboxes
and thermoses,

1498
01:10:28,671 --> 01:10:30,536
and I think he was
in a Nike commercial.

1499
01:10:30,573 --> 01:10:32,404
- (screams)
- (pants)

1500
01:10:32,441 --> 01:10:35,035
Those I believe were banned
or pulled from the market.

1501
01:10:35,077 --> 01:10:37,773
There's been countless TV shows
that have parodied "Friday the 13th,"

1502
01:10:37,813 --> 01:10:41,271
- from "MADtv."
- Man: Jason Takes NASA.

1503
01:10:41,317 --> 01:10:43,751
Yeah, we've done a bunch
of "Friday the 13th" parodies.

1504
01:10:43,786 --> 01:10:47,415
The first thing we did was
a"Horror Movie Big Brother."

1505
01:10:47,456 --> 01:10:49,219
(chainsaw whirring)

1506
01:10:49,258 --> 01:10:51,385
We did a Scooby gang
investigates the mystery

1507
01:10:51,427 --> 01:10:53,292
- of Camp Crystal Lake.
- Zoinks!

1508
01:10:53,329 --> 01:10:55,263
When it gets referenced
on "The Simpsons"

1509
01:10:55,298 --> 01:10:57,596
or "South Park," that's like
your proudest moment.

1510
01:10:57,633 --> 01:10:58,827
(screams)
Run!

1511
01:10:58,868 --> 01:11:02,269
I love the fact that "The Simpsons"
have Jason and Freddy.

1512
01:11:02,305 --> 01:11:04,967
- They should be here by now.
- Ah, what are you gonna do?

1513
01:11:05,007 --> 01:11:07,601
- (switches channel)
- When he got that MTV Movie Award,

1514
01:11:07,643 --> 01:11:10,635
it was absolutely invigorating
for all the fans

1515
01:11:10,680 --> 01:11:14,309
and also it was like, " Where have
we landed exactly as a society?"

1516
01:11:14,350 --> 01:11:16,614
We're giving a Lifetime
Achievement Award

1517
01:11:16,652 --> 01:11:19,348
to a masked predator.

1518
01:11:19,388 --> 01:11:21,356
Shortly after we did
"Jason Takes Manhattan,"

1519
01:11:21,390 --> 01:11:24,450
I was asked to do
"The Arsenio Hall Show"

1520
01:11:24,493 --> 01:11:26,085
in costume as a guest.

1521
01:11:26,128 --> 01:11:29,029
He pulled the whole interview off
by talking to someone who doesn't speak.

1522
01:11:29,065 --> 01:11:31,124
How are you?

1523
01:11:35,271 --> 01:11:37,739
- That's good.
- One of the rare things I've ever done

1524
01:11:37,773 --> 01:11:40,037
in full costume
besides the movie.

1525
01:11:40,076 --> 01:11:41,668
Miska:
Snow globes,

1526
01:11:41,711 --> 01:11:43,542
there's dolls,

1527
01:11:43,579 --> 01:11:47,538
there's even a haunted house
at Universal Studios in Florida

1528
01:11:47,583 --> 01:11:49,107
and in Hollywood.

1529
01:11:49,151 --> 01:11:53,110
One of the greatest thrills
that I've had as a Jason fan

1530
01:11:53,155 --> 01:11:56,454
was going to the Universal
Horror Nights last year.

1531
01:11:56,492 --> 01:11:59,689
Jason Voorhees is running after you.
It's a real guy

1532
01:11:59,729 --> 01:12:03,426
in the whole costume.
I kind of pooped my pants a little bit.

1533
01:12:03,466 --> 01:12:06,162
Hi, I'm John Murdy,
creative director of Universal Studios'

1534
01:12:06,202 --> 01:12:08,693
Hollywood's Halloween Horror Nights
and right now we are standing

1535
01:12:08,738 --> 01:12:12,674
in front of the Crystal Lake cabin
from "Friday the 13th: Camp Blood."

1536
01:12:12,708 --> 01:12:15,472
When you're designing
a haunted attraction like this,

1537
01:12:15,511 --> 01:12:17,376
there's basically three things
you look for.

1538
01:12:17,413 --> 01:12:19,813
One is that the property has legs.

1539
01:12:19,849 --> 01:12:21,976
Second is that
the characters are something

1540
01:12:22,018 --> 01:12:25,385
that you can achieve with actors,
and the third is that the environments

1541
01:12:25,421 --> 01:12:28,754
are strong and easily recognizable.
And "Friday the 13th" has all three.

1542
01:12:28,791 --> 01:12:31,191
So we were very lucky
when we worked with New Line,

1543
01:12:31,227 --> 01:12:33,559
we were able to get
all three of those properties

1544
01:12:33,596 --> 01:12:36,690
and basically turn our theme park
into a living horror movie.

1545
01:12:36,732 --> 01:12:40,031
In this case, he's got
a poor victim stuck in this vise.

1546
01:12:40,069 --> 01:12:43,004
His head's in the vise. Jason
comes in and gives the vise a crank.

1547
01:12:43,039 --> 01:12:45,599
We have a triggered audio effect
that sounds like his bones

1548
01:12:45,641 --> 01:12:47,108
in his skull are crushing,

1549
01:12:47,143 --> 01:12:50,738
and we tied this
into water spritz effect

1550
01:12:50,780 --> 01:12:53,214
so that the guests think "eye goo"

1551
01:12:53,249 --> 01:12:56,082
is shooting out
of the victim onto them.

1552
01:12:56,118 --> 01:12:58,780
This is for the wheelchair victim
that has the machete in his head.

1553
01:12:58,821 --> 01:13:01,187
Again, there's a secret door
for Jason back here

1554
01:13:01,223 --> 01:13:03,157
so he can make
a dramatic entrance,

1555
01:13:03,192 --> 01:13:06,252
and this poor guy
that you think is dead leaps to life.

1556
01:13:06,295 --> 01:13:09,321
When you're designing an attraction like
"Friday the 13th: Camp Blood,"

1557
01:13:09,365 --> 01:13:12,129
for us, what we really want
to do is we wanna deliver

1558
01:13:12,168 --> 01:13:14,329
to the fans
all their favorite kills

1559
01:13:14,370 --> 01:13:16,361
from the "Friday the 13th" series.

1560
01:13:16,405 --> 01:13:18,737
So this is a kill
from "Freddy vs. Jason."

1561
01:13:18,774 --> 01:13:20,935
This is the guy who gets
his back broken in half.

1562
01:13:20,976 --> 01:13:24,104
There's a performer that's laying here
with his head against the bed.

1563
01:13:24,146 --> 01:13:26,307
Jason comes storming
into the room.

1564
01:13:26,348 --> 01:13:29,408
He grabs hold of the bed, and he gives
it a good... (makes squashing sound)

1565
01:13:34,323 --> 01:13:36,757
With Jason,
they made countless toys.

1566
01:13:36,792 --> 01:13:39,056
Every year
there's new editions coming out.

1567
01:13:39,095 --> 01:13:40,995
The McFarlane stuff
and the Mezco stuff,

1568
01:13:41,030 --> 01:13:43,294
they all look great.
They're really well-sculpted,

1569
01:13:43,332 --> 01:13:46,130
articulated, awesome looking.
They're well-painted.

1570
01:13:46,168 --> 01:13:48,398
Who would have thought
there would be Jason dolls?

1571
01:13:50,272 --> 01:13:53,264
There was a great book
that came out a couple of years ago:

1572
01:13:53,309 --> 01:13:57,006
"Crystal Lake Memories"
about "Friday the 13th."

1573
01:13:57,046 --> 01:13:59,640
Peter Bracke did a great job.

1574
01:13:59,682 --> 01:14:02,242
He interviewed a lot of us
in the series,

1575
01:14:02,284 --> 01:14:06,050
from producers, directors
to actors, of course.

1576
01:14:06,088 --> 01:14:08,955
And it covers the series
from A to Z.

1577
01:14:08,991 --> 01:14:12,290
It was so fun to have come
to the book signing

1578
01:14:12,328 --> 01:14:14,956
and to see all the people

1579
01:14:14,997 --> 01:14:16,589
that are now a part of

1580
01:14:16,632 --> 01:14:18,293
this whole "Friday the 13th"
phenomenon.

1581
01:14:19,902 --> 01:14:21,529
It was a party for the launch

1582
01:14:21,570 --> 01:14:24,596
of the "Crystal Lake Memories" book,

1583
01:14:24,640 --> 01:14:26,608
and we signed all
of the books.

1584
01:14:26,642 --> 01:14:28,542
And then of course
Jason showed up

1585
01:14:28,577 --> 01:14:30,169
and cut the cake
with a machete,

1586
01:14:30,212 --> 01:14:32,339
and that was awfully fun.

1587
01:14:32,381 --> 01:14:34,281
An iconic brand
has been built.

1588
01:14:34,316 --> 01:14:37,114
Everybody knows Jason.

1589
01:14:37,153 --> 01:14:38,882
Everybody, all ages.

1590
01:14:38,921 --> 01:14:40,616
It's all over the world.

1591
01:14:40,656 --> 01:14:43,557
At Halloween,
there's always gonna be some kid

1592
01:14:43,592 --> 01:14:45,890
down the hall
wearing a hockey mask.

1593
01:14:45,928 --> 01:14:47,953
There's at least one kid
who comes down your street

1594
01:14:47,997 --> 01:14:49,897
who is Jason Voorhees,

1595
01:14:49,932 --> 01:14:51,957
and the funny thing is
he's up there with Santa Claus

1596
01:14:52,001 --> 01:14:53,832
in the sense
that everybody knows who it is.

1597
01:14:53,869 --> 01:14:55,359
Jason is a big icon.

1598
01:14:55,404 --> 01:14:57,429
I had a trick-or-treater
come to my house...

1599
01:14:57,473 --> 01:14:59,134
a little kid dressed as Jason.

1600
01:14:59,175 --> 01:15:01,143
And I went,
"I worked with him."

1601
01:15:01,177 --> 01:15:04,078
And the kid kind of looked at me
like he didn't understand.

1602
01:15:04,113 --> 01:15:06,547
And I asked my nephew,
'cause he's 13,

1603
01:15:06,582 --> 01:15:08,948
I said, "What is that?"
He goes, "That's the Jason mask."

1604
01:15:08,984 --> 01:15:11,452
And I said, " You know
I'm in one of those movies?"

1605
01:15:11,487 --> 01:15:14,888
And he said, " Oh, I've never
seen any of those movies,

1606
01:15:14,924 --> 01:15:16,721
but I know all about Jason."

1607
01:15:16,759 --> 01:15:18,852
In hindsight, it seems silly
there wouldn't be a backlash.

1608
01:15:18,894 --> 01:15:20,361
The critics were outraged.

1609
01:15:20,396 --> 01:15:22,921
Gene Siskel launched a letter-writing
campaign to Paramount.

1610
01:15:22,965 --> 01:15:24,990
"Friday the 13th:
The Final Chapter,"

1611
01:15:25,034 --> 01:15:27,730
an immoral and reprehensible
piece of trash...

1612
01:15:27,770 --> 01:15:30,671
When Roger Ebert said
that "Friday the 13th" was

1613
01:15:30,706 --> 01:15:33,573
"an immoral and reprehensible
piece of trash,"

1614
01:15:33,609 --> 01:15:37,101
I thought, " Two thumbs up.
Gotta see it." (laughs)

1615
01:15:37,146 --> 01:15:39,273
Kratka:
There's just so much in our culture

1616
01:15:39,315 --> 01:15:42,773
that gets labeled things
unnecessarily

1617
01:15:42,818 --> 01:15:44,285
or just unjustifiably.

1618
01:15:44,320 --> 01:15:46,720
And I think "Friday the 13th" s
were just...

1619
01:15:46,755 --> 01:15:48,245
they're scary movies.

1620
01:15:48,290 --> 01:15:51,123
As film critics,
shame on them for not appreciating

1621
01:15:51,160 --> 01:15:54,857
the fact that they are
artistic entertainment vehicles

1622
01:15:54,897 --> 01:15:57,798
for a very defined demographic.

1623
01:15:57,833 --> 01:16:00,563
We have fun reading reviews.
We know what they're gonna be like,

1624
01:16:00,603 --> 01:16:04,369
and especially if someone gets
particularly bitchy and clever,

1625
01:16:04,406 --> 01:16:07,432
it's great. In a way it's sort of like
the "Friday the 13th" movie itself:

1626
01:16:07,476 --> 01:16:10,468
if they're clever in the way
they're trying to kill you, you cheer.

1627
01:16:10,512 --> 01:16:12,309
What's more appealing
than forbidden fruit?

1628
01:16:12,348 --> 01:16:14,509
That's the oldest story
that there is.

1629
01:16:14,550 --> 01:16:16,780
So when you say
to a young 13-year-old,

1630
01:16:16,819 --> 01:16:20,778
"You can't go see that movie, young man.
It's a piece of immoral trash,"

1631
01:16:20,823 --> 01:16:24,452
I'm pretty confident that's the first
thing the 13-year-old's gonna go do.

1632
01:16:24,493 --> 01:16:28,452
As long as nobody's going out
and doing nothing crazy...

1633
01:16:28,497 --> 01:16:31,227
they never had to put
"Don't try this at home"

1634
01:16:31,267 --> 01:16:33,394
on the screen... so it's all fun.

1635
01:16:33,435 --> 01:16:35,903
It's not attracting psychos to it.

1636
01:16:35,938 --> 01:16:39,499
It really does attract

1637
01:16:39,541 --> 01:16:43,272
a very respectful
group of people.

1638
01:16:43,312 --> 01:16:46,406
Jason can survive anything,
even bad reviews.

1639
01:16:46,448 --> 01:16:49,781
If you're taking these films
too seriously,

1640
01:16:49,818 --> 01:16:52,343
you should probably
go have a Valium

1641
01:16:52,388 --> 01:16:53,980
or do something else.

1642
01:16:54,023 --> 01:16:56,617
I started the Screamfest
Horror Film Festival in 2001

1643
01:16:56,659 --> 01:16:59,321
as a platform to give
independent filmmakers a way

1644
01:16:59,361 --> 01:17:03,161
to further their careers and have
their work be shown to the industry.

1645
01:17:03,198 --> 01:17:05,928
I think some of the films
that we've screened in Screamfest

1646
01:17:05,968 --> 01:17:08,198
definitely have been influenced
by "Friday the 13th."

1647
01:17:08,237 --> 01:17:11,673
Most recently I would say
Adam Green's "Hatchet."

1648
01:17:11,707 --> 01:17:14,039
I think almost any slasher movie

1649
01:17:14,076 --> 01:17:16,943
post-"Friday the 13th"

1650
01:17:16,979 --> 01:17:18,412
kind of tipped their hat to it.

1651
01:17:18,447 --> 01:17:21,678
It's a great independent film.
And it's great to look back

1652
01:17:21,717 --> 01:17:24,277
and... what?
20-some-odd years later

1653
01:17:24,320 --> 01:17:27,187
to look back and see young filmmakers,
like an Adam, up and coming,

1654
01:17:27,222 --> 01:17:30,055
to have a film that's reminiscent
of "Friday the 13th."

1655
01:17:30,092 --> 01:17:31,650
So it's kind of cool.

1656
01:17:31,694 --> 01:17:33,719
I've been to a million conventions

1657
01:17:33,762 --> 01:17:36,230
and I see people
with Jason tattoos.

1658
01:17:37,599 --> 01:17:40,067
It's a lot of fun.

1659
01:17:44,707 --> 01:17:46,231
Come on, it's beautiful.

1660
01:17:46,275 --> 01:17:48,266
We bleed for this shit.

1661
01:17:48,310 --> 01:17:51,871
The fans are open to creating
their own mythology

1662
01:17:51,914 --> 01:17:53,347
about them too.

1663
01:17:53,382 --> 01:17:56,476
Man: He had just received
a surprise postcard from Jason,

1664
01:17:56,518 --> 01:18:00,010
inviting him to take part
in a slayathon.

1665
01:18:00,055 --> 01:18:03,821
Jason doesn't have a star
on the walk of fame.

1666
01:18:03,859 --> 01:18:06,987
This is terrible.
He's been around for 30 years

1667
01:18:07,029 --> 01:18:09,156
and he can't get a star?

1668
01:18:09,198 --> 01:18:11,257
Jason is a star!

1669
01:18:13,902 --> 01:18:16,530
(silent)

1670
01:18:17,973 --> 01:18:19,941
Oh, sorry.
I didn't know anybody

1671
01:18:19,975 --> 01:18:23,172
was using this room.

1672
01:18:27,549 --> 01:18:29,881
(girl screaming)

1673
01:18:29,918 --> 01:18:32,716
Okay, I admit it.
I love this stuff.

1674
01:18:32,755 --> 01:18:35,417
But as we've seen,
so do millions of others.

1675
01:18:35,457 --> 01:18:38,790
I mean, after all a good killer
is never out of style, right?

1676
01:18:38,827 --> 01:18:41,523
Which is exactly why the original
terrifying legend

1677
01:18:41,563 --> 01:18:44,430
of Jason Voorhees
is being reimagined

1678
01:18:44,466 --> 01:18:47,867
and repackaged
for a whole new generation of fans.

1679
01:18:47,903 --> 01:18:50,963
It's exciting to see Jason up
to his old tricks.

1680
01:18:51,006 --> 01:18:53,201
(girl screaming)

1681
01:18:56,311 --> 01:18:58,438
So now after all of this time,

1682
01:18:58,480 --> 01:19:01,244
playing around with Jason

1683
01:19:01,283 --> 01:19:02,841
